commit_message:
Update aggregate should not allow duplicated names

It is not allow to create 2 aggregates with the same name
but if update an existing one with a name already used
by other aggregate that check should be made.
This patch doesn't allow to change the name to an existing
one.

Change-Id: Icfe315594beaec94229e5a4a4c1bb80fc366b66e
Closes-Bug: #1288296
(cherry picked from commit 2b2decfd1b5b0d68813bc7e5b5e4349a1ab592aa)

commit_message:
Fix difference between mysql & psql of flavor-show

If you create a new flavor using a deleted flavorid,
the result of flavor-show is different between mysql and psql.

This issue is caused by the different processing for index in each db.

We need to specify the sort-type to avoid the issue.

Change-Id: Ib1029e80c1b981e1ec86d954b63f83650c9b1cc1
Closes-Bug: #1288636
(cherry picked from commit 4bbb4d88595cfd5f75528d8789be94d0ec9fbe62)

commit_message:
libvirt: Custom disk_bus setting is being lost on hard_reboot

Currently, a non-default disk_bus setting of and image will not be used,
when powering on an instance (or _hard_reboot).

hard_reboot() should use image_meta, if it exist, when constructing
the disk_info

Closes-Bug: #1255449

(cherry picked from commit 0fe3001d639df81ae4e5f77bcfc32bc1bffb014e)

Conflicts:
	nova/virt/libvirt/driver.py

Change-Id: I477f69c47515ad22165421b4d23ac865c7869873

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-09-19 06:20:28.000000000', 'message': 'Add missing "load url from future" in a container template

The modified template uses new syntax for the URL template tag,
but doesn't load the new syntax definition, as required by Django.
This leads to errors when trying to render that template.

Change-Id: I42ddb39cad62b1be0cad81d4758412a981be461e
Closes-bug: #1331271
(cherry picked from commit 8c711e8f6b80bebe9ad49eb6a718b2aba0e2b11b)
'}]
commit_message:
Add missing "load url from future" in a container template

The modified template uses new syntax for the URL template tag,
but doesn't load the new syntax definition, as required by Django.
This leads to errors when trying to render that template.

Change-Id: I42ddb39cad62b1be0cad81d4758412a981be461e
Closes-bug: #1331271
(cherry picked from commit 8c711e8f6b80bebe9ad49eb6a718b2aba0e2b11b)

keystone discovery fallback support

version discovery and sessions aren't supported by all external
auth systems. this patch adds a fallback when discovery does not
work.

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-09-13 00:39:57.000000000', 'message': "Fixes network_get_all_by_host to use indexes

The OR in the subquery was constructed in a way that didn't allow
the fixed_ips without instances allocated to be filtered out. It
also had an unnecessary join through virtual interfaces. We have a
denormalized field for instance_uuid with an index in the fixed_ips
table that we can use. This patch removes the unnecessary join and
ads an extra filter inside the OR to reject fixed_ips without
instances. In my test with 300000 fixed ips, this reduced the query
time from about 2.5 seconds to less than 0.01 seconds.

Change-Id: I26fb0dfaf5ff64bd70c947982de4ec1728c84856
Resolves-bug: #1369009
"}]
commit_message:
Fixes network_get_all_by_host to use indexes

The OR in the subquery was constructed in a way that didn't allow
the fixed_ips without instances allocated to be filtered out. It
also had an unnecessary join through virtual interfaces. We have a
denormalized field for instance_uuid with an index in the fixed_ips
table that we can use. This patch removes the unnecessary join and
ads an extra filter inside the OR to reject fixed_ips without
instances. In my test with 300000 fixed ips, this reduced the query
time from about 2.5 seconds to less than 0.01 seconds.

Change-Id: I26fb0dfaf5ff64bd70c947982de4ec1728c84856
Resolves-bug: #1369009

commit_message:
Make rescheduling of l3 agent more resilient

In order to make l3 agent restart more resilient
and idempotent do:

1) delete agent after resource is stopped and
all the stuff is cleaned up

2) reschedule not only dead routers/networks but also
orphaned routers/networks

3) enclose get_pid_list_for_ns_list function argument
in cleanup function into double quoutes
or it will use only the first argument
and will not work with several networks

Change-Id: I06a89f0015c8f188d212995ed0652c5ee2cc1c47
Related-Bug: #1371550

commit_message:
Fix unstable assertion in test_cinder_endpoints

In simple_read_only.test_cinder.test_cinder_endpoints, the test case
assumes that the first table of 'cinder endpoints' always ['nova',
'Value']. However, it is sometimes wrong.
So in this commit, the test verifies that they have 2 or more headers
and has a 'Value' header.

Change-Id: Idb3f2ebc6b7e05178621ac3701b7c3d02e1d7591
Closes-Bug: #1363018
Closes-Bug: #1362703

commit_message:
Cleanup and adding timing to lockutils logging

* Cleanup lockutils logging by showing lock name and function in
same line.  The enables easier parsing of information related to lock
acquisition from logs.

* Logs time a thread spent waiting on locks, as well as time spent
holding locks.  This will make it easier to debug suboptimal locking.

Change-Id: Ic310d84eb1ed75cc1c21c3d7861b4a3927ebaf23

commit_message:
Migrate test_server_cfn_init to tempest clients

Migrate the test and change OrchestrationScenarioTest used by the test.
This is a part of the migrating all scenario tests to using tempest own
clients.

Change-Id: Iafc1b021fe8a9a5daa0e2d7eef0542b7929c415a
Partially-implements: bp:tempest-client-scenarios

commit_message:
Fix Cluster-Create and Cluster-Show Response

the refactoring in Ie1ac42d61e920ac8ea1ebab35c2db096fd313077
broke the responses for the aforementioned commands,
resulting in stacktraces.

Closes-Bug: #1368982

commit_message:
Add the redis opts to the generate sample shell script

* Fix the redis opts typo in setup.cfg
* Fix the default value type for reconnect_sleep in redis
* add the redis to oslo.config.generator.rc

Change-Id: Ibd439e2bdaa46ddf21802724f9fe7fb6f2b61bc5

commit_message:
Add _ prefix to local variables

A lot of __init__ methods were assigning
values to attributes that were not prefixed with
a single underscore, the underscore prefix has been
added as needed.

Closes-Bug: 1239834
Change-Id: Idf7e29b413187f726fb9f8a85959f948db6d669c

commit_message:
Removes claim_id param in v1.0

This change fixes backwards compatibility for claims
by formating the messages obtained from the storage.

commit_message:
Don't clear _mounted_shares list in remoteFS while updating

This fix makes the updating of the _mounted_shares list in
remoteFS more of an atomic operation.  Previously this list
would be cleared, then rebuilt.  That allowed a race
condition where operations that took place during this
update would have a list of 0 shares to work with.

Closes-Bug: #1366083
cherry-picked from commit 9cc9cf111ef8a0265df5323fecaed12b0dabe312
Change-Id: I740d8f1b87db911242326a38ff398b81c5974cea

Looks like a reasonable starting point, I made some inline comments, but also have a couple of general comments:

1. Personally I'd be happy to live with REPLICATION rather than changing to RUGGEDIZE everywhere, or at least to hold off making the change until I can see how it all gets fleshed out. We still have ReplicationExceptions and lots of comments referring to replication e.g. in ssync - seems like resolving all that inconsistent terminology could become a distraction to getting the functionality right.

2. reconstructor.py duplicates a lot of replicator.py - did you consider subclassing, or creating a common superclass? I appreciate the two will diverge as TODOs get done but still seems like there is scope to re-use some code. Thanks Alistair... to your comments:

- didn't see the exception verbiage that would have to change as well.  for the initial check-in I'm nor married to the crazy new verb but I think keeping REPLICATION will cause confusion later as that's not what the receiver will be doing - it will be "making durable" and the how depends on the policy so that's why I wanted to move away from that verb.  If you're not willing to go +2 without changing it back I'm not going to argue, it's too early for that :)
- yes, I did consider sub-classing or something similar and call that out in the design but as you noted, the reason I haven't yet is because there's still so many TODOs I wanted to keep the basics very simple until things are mostly in place, then go back and see where it makes sense to break out commonality.  Otherwise the effort now may just need to be reversed it one the current unknowns ventures off into areas of the code that we don't expect.  Would much rather keep it as is for now and if you have some cycles to spend there's 1 of 4 big things in the reconstructor that I would love for you to tackle.  I'll see if I can catch you on IRC or maybe email as I'll be at a conference all next week - thanks again!'}, {'account_id': 7847, 'date': '2014-09-16 08:36:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1

commit_message:
Early framework for the EC Reconstructor

Patch that adds the reconstructor daemon and a placeholder for
tests.  There are several TODOs related to Trello items that
can be worked on independently by various developers, thus
looking to land this patch on the integration branch to enable
that work.

Sleep on the verb RUGGEDIZE, it may grow on you :) We can always
change it later.... and likely will

Change-Id: Ic203cb313193fc4b0e557b299ea11d5d45e80d24
Implements: blueprint ec-reconstructor

commit_message:
Set default API_WORKERS

Set the API_WORKERS default to control memory usage. Maximum is nproc / 2 and
minimum is 2.

* Also updates https://review.openstack.org/#/c/117517/ to remove the
  conditional test as API_WORKERS should always be set.
* Update https://review.openstack.org/#/c/109058/ for ceilometer to use API_WORKERS

The following reviews can move forward either as-is or with minor tweaks:
* Keystone: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/121384/ - remove the if check
* Swift: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/121456/ - unabandon, the default
  to 1 is fine, or remove it to match the others.
* Trove: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/121438/ - remove the if check

https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/devstack-workers has the details

Change-Id: Id28d72ebf01c88b7df301edf7d1dd7ec23fcd0d6

commit_message:
Remove ramdisk build option for Ironic agent driver

This was overlooked when Ironic gained the ability to set
IRONIC_BUILD_DEPLOY_RAMDISK in devstack-gate.

Change-Id: Id8f8dced716baca7e6ab8a209cddd59bb6783673

commit_message:
Catch Exception instead of RuntimeError for driver

The latest version of stevedore re-raises the real exception instead of
raising RuntimeError. This patch replaces `RuntimeError` with
`Exception` and catches connection failures correctly.

In addition, this conenction failures are now logged.

Change-Id: I39c64221180f25be0d31134f3a16a894ca2dd51f

commit_message:
Ensure user metadata mapped for instance notifications

Fixes bug 1284073

For pollster-originated samples related to instances, we apply a
mapping to the user metadata so as to ensure that there are no
embedded periods in metadata keys and also to exclude any metadata
not matching the configured reserved namespace.

Now this logic is also applied to user metadata for samples derived
from instance-related notifications in order to avoid failures when
persisting these data in mongodb.

(cherry picked from commit ddeb54bb0d2c4203332a5ecc09a4aedfce353a4c)
Change-Id: I77eab59023fa23c5879b05c948bd4cb1db7fa177

commit_message:
Represent memory unit in string

Enable unit representation for property 'mem_size' in
Compute node.
1. valid units are: MB or GB, MB being default choice
2. allow space separator(s) between number and unit
3. no space between number and unit is also allowed
4. use default value if no property mem_size is not given
5. use default value if mem_size value is not specified
6. default value is 1024 MB

Blue Print: Represent memory unit in string

Change-Id: I0850a6dcb627f1a4bb4f24242b530fa42f598ce3

commit_message:
Represent memory unit in string

Enable unit representation for property 'mem_size' in
Compute node.
1. valid units are: MB or GB, MB being default choice
2. allow space separator(s) between number and unit
3. no space between number and unit is also allowed
4. use default value if no property mem_size is not given
5. default value is 1024 MB

Blue Print: Represent memory unit in string

Change-Id: Id1f59eb4bac0d8c31cdbdb9845525de9ddb948d1

(2 comments)

Swami, thanks for addressing my comments.

The biggest problem with this patch now is that it has too many themes all mixed together.  As a reviewer, I felt the need to pick apart the changes to understand what the themes were.  Rather than pass this burden on to other potential reviewers, I took a little extra time to split it up.  Please consider looking over this chain of commits [1].  The end result is equivalent to what you have in this patch set but each patch set will be easier to review and merge.

Large monolithic changes have all kinds of problems.  Reviewers often avoid them or put them off.  When they do get around to reviewing them, having multiple themes in the patch puts extra burden on the reviewer, more burden than the sum of the individual themes.  It can hide problems because reviewers get sloppy with large reviews.  Finally, if a problem is found with the patch down the road, it is difficult to understand which theme was responsible for the breakage.

[{'created': '2014-08-15 01:16:46.000000000', 'message': 'Problems with DVR-Router updates after ext-gw set

A few problems with SNAT handling in the l3-agent
and scheduler have been found.

- A fix has been found for when a router is updated
after a gateway-set has been done where SNAT namespaces
are created on all nodes (CNs and NNs).
Closes-bug: #1356734

- Even with no VMs present, qrouter namespaces are being
created when a router is updated after a gateway-set
has been done. TBD.

Change-Id: Iba5668b2717e188d5289ede982bfc1b46f4eeb5b
'}, {'created': '2014-08-15 23:48:02.000000000', 'message': 'Problems with DVR-Router updates after ext-gw set

A few problems with SNAT handling in the l3-agent
and scheduler have been found.

- A fix has been found for when a router is updated
after a gateway-set has been done where SNAT namespaces
are created on all nodes (CNs and NNs).

Fixes the issue of qrouter getting created on
all nodes when router-update happens.

Fixes the issue where SNAT namespace and qrouter
namespace not created when a router-create command
is executed with the gateway - singel REST call.

In all the above cases now the namespaces will be
created only when there is a valid VM in the subnet.

Closes-bug: #1356734
Closes-bug: #1353266

Change-Id: Iba5668b2717e188d5289ede982bfc1b46f4eeb5b
'}, {'created': '2014-08-16 08:38:10.000000000', 'message': 'Problems with DVR-Router updates after ext-gw set

A few problems with SNAT handling in the l3-agent
and scheduler have been found.

- A fix has been found for when a router is updated
after a gateway-set has been done where SNAT namespaces
are created on all nodes (CNs and NNs).

Fixes the issue of qrouter getting created on
all nodes when router-update happens.

Fixes the issue where SNAT namespace and qrouter
namespace not created when a router-create command
is executed with the gateway - singel REST call.

In all the above cases now the namespaces will be
created only when there is a valid VM in the subnet.

Closes-bug: #1356734
Closes-bug: #1353266
Closes-bug: #1356639

'}, {'created': '2014-08-22 21:47:46.000000000', 'message': 'Problems with DVR-Router updates after ext-gw set

When SNAT namespaces and Router namespaces are
created, the scheduler identifies the agent type,
the plugin checks for dvr related port
availability and agent creates the respective
namespaces.

The router update actions such as

  1. Interface Add/Delete
  2. Extra_Routes Add/Delete
  3. External Gateway Set/Clear

was triggering the initial router scheduling
and namespace creation.

But when a router is created along with Gateway,
this action does not trigger a router update.
So the scheduler was not aware about the gateway
being added to the router and so it was not
creating the right namespaces. This issue is
fixed with this patch.

Also the plugin check for dvr related port was
returing "true" even when there were no valid
subnets associated with a router.
This patch fixes this issue and so now the
qrouter namespaces will only be created in DVR
nodes that host the VMs.

"qrouters" created for SNAT support on DVR_SNAT
node even if there is no VMs is an Exception,
that is a known behavior.

The agent was creating SNAT namespaces on all
nodes including DVR and DVR_SNAT nodes even
though the binding was done for the DVR_SNAT
node. This patch also fixes this issue.

Closes-bug: #1356734
Closes-bug: #1353266
Closes-bug: #1356639

Co-Authored-By: Swaminathan Vasudevan <swaminathan.vasudevan@hp.com>

Change-Id: Iba5668b2717e188d5289ede982bfc1b46f4eeb5b

'}, {'created': '2014-08-25 19:38:05.000000000', 'message': 'Refactor the DVR scheduler to get rid of hints

When SNAT namespaces and Router namespaces are
created, the scheduler identifies the agent type,
the plugin checks for dvr related port
availability and agent creates the respective
namespaces.

The router update actions such as

  1. Interface Add/Delete
  2. Extra_Routes Add/Delete
  3. External Gateway Set/Clear

was triggering the initial router scheduling
and namespace creation based on the hints that
was passed in.

But when a router is created along with Gateway,
this action does not trigger a router update,
since there was no hints being passed during the
create operation.

Hence the scheduler was not aware about the gateway
being added to the router and so it was not
creating the right namespaces.

By refactoring the DVR scheduler code to not
depend on the hints fixed this issue and it made
the flow more predictable.

Closes-bug: #1353266
Closes-bug: #1356639

Co-Authored-By: Swaminathan Vasudevan <swaminathan.vasudevan@hp.com>

Change-Id: Iba5668b2717e188d5289ede982bfc1b46f4eeb5b

commit_message:
Avoid an extra database query in schedule_snat_router

bind_snat_servicenode already knows the chosen_agent.  By waiting
until after it is called, we can use it to avoid another db query.

Closes-bug: #1353266
Closes-bug: #1356639
Co-Authored-By: Swaminathan Vasudevan <swaminathan.vasudevan@hp.com>

[{'created': '2014-09-18 22:09:34.000000000', 'message': "Close standard fds in test child process

The std fd's are shared with parent processes, which makes testr think
that we still have test workers, even though this isn't a test
process, its a live server.

Change-Id: I516a6a9bd9a98abffeb182189038763ea94618f6
Partial-Bug: #1357578

commit_message:
Close standard fds in test child process

The std fd's are shared with parent processes, which makes testr think
that we still have test workers, even though this isn't a test
process, its a live server.

Change-Id: I516a6a9bd9a98abffeb182189038763ea94618f6
Partial-Bug: #1357578

commit_message:
Revert iSCSI Target objects as independent objects

Removing from gate queue since failing unit tests

The second half of this code didn't make it in, so this is essentially
dead code. We'll readd this code back in Kilo.

This reverts commit d10fb796f491152486e394481e920479bab9e3d1.

Closes-Bug: #1365516
Change-Id: Ia4b3b4ef4a7b6f3829fe576ec370b6d74a7bc922

[{'created': '2014-04-03 04:49:56.000000000', 'message': "Message was sended to wrong node with use zmq as rpc_backend

When use zmq as rpc_backend of nova, message cannot
send to correct node because the queues we got
from matchmaker maybe is wrong. To fix this problem,
as server item in oslo.messaging.target.Target object,
and the server item is the correct node which message
should be send to, we use Target object to create
queues. Then, message can be send to the 'real' node
which shoule received it.

Closes-bug: #1301723

commit_message:
Message was send to wrong node with use zmq as rpc_backend

zmq: Send message to correct endpoint for directed messages

If set the zmq driver needs to use the topic.server
attribute to ensure that messages directed to a
specific endpoint are sent to the correct server rather
than being randomly sent to endpoints advertising the
required topic.

Change-Id: If63235640e0b8e6ec8690a4edaefa1b303705ac6
Closes-bug: #1301723

subject: Whenever Q_USE_SECGROUP was set to True in local.conf, lib/neutron script was not resetting the nova firewall driver.

commit_message:
Whenever Q_USE_SECGROUP was set to True in local.conf, lib/neutron script was
not resetting the nova firewall driver.

The neutron script was fixed to change the nova firewall_driver to NoopFirewallDriver
whenever Q_USE_SECGROUP was set to True

This closes bug: 1248381
"nova firewall set to IpTablesFirewallDriver when neutron sec groups enabled"

Change-Id: Iaf42a5b0e7492d231327d980afb5d1ea8928369b

commit_message:
There was a mismatch in case when referring to security groups between ml2 and
ovs.

ML2 was referring to the security group directive as SECURITYGROUP whereas
OVS is referring it as securitygroup

Fix was to change the ML2 to refer to securitygroup

This closes bug : 1248385

Change-Id: I4351ee1aba5f524427523c7419d4430db3f476ac

commit_message:
Set enable_ipset to False by default

The default is currently set to True which is not upgrade friendly in
that anyone upgrading to the most recent Neutron code immediately has to
have the ipset binary installed or their commands fail.

It seems like we should set this to false by default (as a safe default)
and allow users to opt in since it is really an optimization.

This patch recently broke TripleO CI for this very reason.

Change-Id: Icea7869901483392c55dea27cc711619aba62376
Closes-bug: #1369386

commit_message:
Reduce redundant parameter of some commands in CLI

When deleting an alarm, we use "ceilometer alarm-delete -a <ALARM_ID>",
unlike other deleting commands of openstack, the parameter-a/--alarm_id
is redundant. The similar situations exist in showing alarm, geting alarm
state, showing resource and so on.
It is more easy to use for reducing these parameters.

New behaviour:

$ ceilometer help alarm-show
usage: ceilometer alarm-show [<ALARM_ID>]

Show an alarm.

Positional arguments:
  <ALARM_ID>  ID of the alarm to show.

$ ceilometer alarm-show
alarm_id should not be empty

$ ceilometer alarm-show abcde
Not Found (HTTP 404)

$ ceilometer alarm-show -a abcde
-a is obsolete! See help for more details.
Not Found (HTTP 404)

$ ceilometer alarm-show --alarm_id abcde
--alarm_id is obsolete! See help for more details.
Not Found (HTTP 404)

Co-Authored-By: Nejc Saje <nsaje@redhat.com>
Change-Id: I1fbc85aa253929bfbb5e73ed834a725b9cf828b4
Closes-bug: #1268557

commit_message:
clean up swift middleware to avoid unicode errors

the swift middleware does not handle environment variables correctly.
this is causing ceilometer errors to be thrown in syslogs in the
check-swift-dsvm-full tests.

this patch adds in unicode support.

Closes-Bug: #1369124
Change-Id: Icf0874efcc69d9889df591b2cb4bbdd3930eaf68

commit_message:
Adding common.utils.exception_to_str() to avoid encoding issue

1. Ported common.utils.exception_to_str() back to glance_store.
2. Used exception_to_str() to consistently cast the exception to avoid
potential encoding issue.

Change-Id: I398ea0e218ebb37b9041cfe82f18b11e614662bf
Related-Id: I77478a8eeeefd85bf98138156429df53d0a4c079
Signed-off-by: Zhi Yan Liu <zhiyanl@cn.ibm.com>

subject: delete test_security_group_get_no_instances
reviewers: [{'_account_id': 4393, 'name': 'Dan Smith', 'email': 'dms@danplanet.com', 'username': 'danms'}, {'_account_id': 5170, 'name': 'Microsoft Hyper-V CI', 'email': 'hyper-v_ci@microsoft.com', 'username': 'hyper-v-ci', 'tags': ['SERVICE_USER']}, {'_account_id': 6873, 'name': 'Matt Riedemann', 'email': 'mriedem.os@gmail.com', 'username': 'mriedem'}, {'_account_id': 9578, 'name': 'DB Datasets CI', 'email': 'turbo-hipster@lists.rcbops.com', 'username': 'turbo-hipster', 'tags': ['SERVICE_USER']}]
messages:
[{'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2014-09-19 20:45:44.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2014-09-19 20:50:50.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

I'm OK with this given the test was added before we had concurrent test workers.  When looking at this bug initially, the subunit logs were running various compute manager tests that touch the DB at the same time as this so the fact that the unit test is messing with the DB session seems risky.

And as pointed out, we're not doing anything with the error so we're really testing sqlalchemy/ORM here rather than something in nova so we're probably testing too deep.  I can't think of a better way to test the same thing though, so maybe Dan has thoughts."}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2014-09-19 21:46:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-2

This is testing that our join_columns does the right thing when fetching security_groups. If that breaks, it's *very* expensive because you could potentially join every instance in the system that shares a security group.

This was (and still is) the only way I know of to test that the thing is or isn't loaded after the call that works on SQLAlchemy 0.8 and 0.9.

We can (1) figure out a better way to do it or (2) make this less specific about the get_session() call so that it passes. However, I think doing either of those without figuring out what other test is changing things such that the get_session() call isn't what we expect it to be is just ignoring the real issue."}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2014-09-19 22:06:34.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]
revisions:
[{'created': '2014-09-19 20:45:44.000000000', 'message': "delete test_security_group_get_no_instances

This test is very much not in line with the rest of the db_api
tests. It actually manipulates session, which none of the rest of them
do. The test boils down to testing for a specific sqla exception,
though there is no code in the rest of nova that does anything with
that kind of exception. Also it's definitively racey and has caused a
number of gate resets because something that it is doing with the db
is not safe.

We should just remove it.

Change-Id: I64002dea3c68c18f4e2a2f32ed27d48dcc62d26a
Closes-Bug: #1349147
"}]
commit_message:
delete test_security_group_get_no_instances

This test is very much not in line with the rest of the db_api
tests. It actually manipulates session, which none of the rest of them
do. The test boils down to testing for a specific sqla exception,
though there is no code in the rest of nova that does anything with
that kind of exception. Also it's definitively racey and has caused a
number of gate resets because something that it is doing with the db
is not safe.

We should just remove it.

Change-Id: I64002dea3c68c18f4e2a2f32ed27d48dcc62d26a
Closes-Bug: #1349147

commit_message:
Update to newer Centos7 images

Update to newer Centos7 images as announced at [1].

Changes included:
 * update to GA image
 * respect TMP_DIR for image working directory
 * use suffix-match rather than prefix-match to build RAW_IMAGE name
   to be more robust against weird names
 * partition layout work-arounds not needed any-more, all one
   partition.

Resulting image booted locally with kvm and virtualbox (after
conversion to vdi)

[1] https://www.redhat.com/archives/rdo-list/2014-August/msg00045.html

Closes-Bug: #1363146
Change-Id: Ie24033468b78587ea87188ee1b843b26895798ff

commit_message:
Pin docutils to 0.9.1

Docutils 0.10 breaks manpage generation in sphinx 1.1.3. A fix to
sphinx has been merged, but not yet released (scheduled for dec
24-31). In the mean time, we should pin docutils to 0.9.1.

Similar change was present before as
I157f3c191bfc09d2191a3508d81bcbaea56205a6 but was incorrectly removed by
later requirements syncs.

Closes-Bug: 1091333
Change-Id: I157f3c191bfc09d2191a3508d81bcbaea56205a6

commit_message:
Move over a reflection module that taskflow uses

Taskflow has a quite useful reflection module that it would
appear others would benefit from having access to, so instead
of keeping it in taskflow, move it over to oslo.utils so that
others can benefit from it.

Potential users:

- Oslo.db
- Cinder
- Taskflow (where the code used to exist)
- Others doing name lookup or other reflection functionality

Change-Id: I9fbdd86966afddb862cb7faed2f88298a9f956cf

commit_message:
libvirt: avoid need for lockutils setup running test cases

Some of the firewall/driver test cases rely on lockutils being
setup, so running tests directly fails:

 $ .venv/bin/python -m testtools.run nova.tests.virt.libvirt
 ...snip...
    Traceback (most recent call last):
      File "nova/tests/virt/libvirt/test_driver.py", line 10182, in test_multinic_iptables
        self.fw.prepare_instance_filter(instance_ref, network_info)
      File "nova/virt/firewall.py", line 184, in prepare_instance_filter
        self.refresh_provider_fw_rules()
      File "nova/virt/firewall.py", line 474, in refresh_provider_fw_rules
        self._do_refresh_provider_fw_rules()
      File "nova/openstack/common/lockutils.py", line 267, in inner
        with lock(name, lock_file_prefix, external, lock_path):
      File "/usr/lib64/python2.7/contextlib.py", line 17, in __enter__
        return self.gen.next()
      File "nova/openstack/common/lockutils.py", line 231, in lock
        ext_lock = external_lock(name, lock_file_prefix, lock_path)
      File "nova/openstack/common/lockutils.py", line 180, in external_lock
        lock_file_path = _get_lock_path(name, lock_file_prefix, lock_path)
      File "nova/openstack/common/lockutils.py", line 171, in _get_lock_path
        raise cfg.RequiredOptError('lock_path')
    RequiredOptError: value required for option: lock_path

The first workaround is to launch using (which run_tests.sh does)

 $ python -m nova.openstack.common.lockutils

but it is nicer to developers if we just avoid the need for using
external lock files during the test suite execution entirely. This
can be done by mocking the 'external_lock' method to use a transient
semaphore instead of external lock file on disk.

Closes-bug: #1369973
Change-Id: I3dcdf6353986ff35c7237644f467ee7e98423f76

commit_message:
Pull in commits to stabilize CI

Our CI system seems to be pron to some timing errors, pulling in
fixes for two of these should give us some improvements while we wait on
the fixes to merge upstream.

Change-Id: Ia50953d2a1cb21dc94787660cd66019239b64ece

commit_message:
Remove neutron cherry pick to disable ipset

Removes cherry pick for https://review.openstack.org/#/c/121434/
which got a -2 (so I abandoned it).

TripleO works now with ipset because we landed
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/121435/ instead which
simply installs the ipset package.

Change-Id: I03301091b041c60dfbe5ac93810fbfeb35d0e671

commit_message:
Add a cherrypick utility function

Adds a function to cherry pick a specific Gerrit refspec.

As we are having to cherry pick quite a few commits
to keep TripleO CI running while things creep through
the gate this should be helpful.

Change-Id: I904ef29960d26fd467797d6e660fb5032f4ae310

commit_message:
NSX: log request body to NSX as debug

Previously we never logged the request body that we sent to NSX. This makes
things hard to debug when issues arise as we don't actually log the body of
the request that we made. This patch adds the body to our issue request log
statement.

Change-Id: I7d98e3d844ebe565fb5919aac3f9afd5b4040e69
Closes-bug: 1360394
(cherry picked from commit 2bc898ff7a18928e94eb81b24dc99d5cb20eae8a)

commit_message:
Revert "Remove PYTHONHASHSEED=0 from tox.ini"

This reverts commit a10f768ac1d1ef3cc36dadcb6eba16a7e376b499.

This reverts https://review.openstack.org/#/c/116744 . It seems
that this change was pre-mature; most (all?) Ironic jobs are
now failing in a related manner.

Closes-Bug: 1371755
Change-Id: I910a349226ed04aae0add92c3a87c1d15a7d7e02

'}, {'created': '2014-09-08 16:43:13.000000000', 'message': "Add HA support to the l3 agent

* Add HA mixins used by RouterInfo and LNAT3Agent
* For HA routers: Internal, external and floating IP addresses are no
  longer configured by the agent. Instead the interfaces and addresses
  are passed to a keepalived configuration, which configures the
  addresses when the router transitions to the master state.
* Only the master instance of the router opens the metadata proxy.
  This happens due to keepalived notification scripts that are
  called upon state transitions.
* Extra routes are handled via keepalived virtual routes and are
  no longer configured by the agent.
* HA routers create a 'HA device' on a VRRP-traffic only HA-network.
* Functional testing: Add two new tests to the L3 agent:
    1) Translation of a router configuration to a keepalived
       configuration.
    2) HA specific events when creating a HA router - Assert that
       keepalived is up, etc.

Change-Id: I83f2a5d2af42164c42773b385ba7b00872eed54e
Implements: blueprint l3-high-availability
Co-Authored-By: Assaf Muller <amuller@redhat.com>
"}, {'created': '2014-09-09 18:32:54.000000000', 'message': "Add HA support to the l3 agent

* For HA routers: Internal, external and floating IP addresses are no

commit_message:
Add HA support to the l3 agent

* Add HA mixins used by RouterInfo and LNAT3Agent
* For HA routers: Internal, external and floating IP addresses are no
  longer configured by the agent. Instead the interfaces and addresses
  are passed to a keepalived configuration, which configures the
  addresses when the router transitions to the master state.
* Only the master instance of the router opens the metadata proxy.
  This happens due to keepalived notification scripts that are
  called upon state transitions.
* Extra routes are handled via keepalived virtual routes and are
  no longer configured by the agent.
* HA routers create a 'HA device' on a VRRP-traffic only HA-network.
* Functional testing: Add two new tests to the L3 agent:
    1) Translation of a router configuration to a keepalived
       configuration.
    2) HA specific events when creating a HA router - Assert that
       keepalived is up, etc.

Change-Id: I83f2a5d2af42164c42773b385ba7b00872eed54e
Implements: blueprint l3-high-availability
Co-Authored-By: Assaf Muller <amuller@redhat.com>

Currently, the VMware driver spawn contains logic to check whether
a block device mapping is provided or not. This branching will either
trigger the logic to boot from an image or to use the volume provided
as the root disk.
However, this implementation doesn't handle the case where the user
wants to boot from an image and attach volumes at the same time.
This patch addresses this issue by checking whether the instance

Closes-Bug: #1271966

commit_message:
(WIP) VMware: Support spawn VM with multiple disks

Currently, the VMware driver spawn contains logic to check whether
a block device mapping is provided or not. This branching will either
trigger the logic to boot from an image or to use the volume provided
as the root disk.
However, this implementation doesn't handle the case where the user
wants to boot from an image and attach volumes at the same time.
This patch addresses this issue by checking whether the instance
contains an image reference.
If an image reference is provided: we boot from image, and potentially we
can add block device mappings to the VM created. Otherwise, we use
the volume provided as the root disk.

Change-Id: I16b7d6803aa8a8cc92852499f0353ca88b86a5f3
Closes-Bug: #1271966

[{'created': '2014-09-12 17:23:00.000000000', 'message': "XenAPI improve post snapshot coalesce detection

The coalesce detection is not working well after this change:
ae2a27ce19f3e24d4a8c713a73e617f4cd71d4b4

The snapshot operation will introduce a new VHD file into the VDI chain,
and in many cases, that would be coalesced during the next SR scan. So
we need to walk the chain after the snapshot has been taken, not before.

This fixes the cause of the mentioned bug, but it doesn't help with
launching the partially corrupted snapshots created because of this bug,
so this only partially fixes the bug.

Change-Id: I0bf7535ae3f7d9e6820f8dc07075892953d80a78

commit_message:
XenAPI improve post snapshot coalesce detection

The coalesce detection is not working well after this change:
ae2a27ce19f3e24d4a8c713a73e617f4cd71d4b4

The snapshot operation will introduce a new VHD file into the VDI chain,
and in many cases, that would be coalesced during the next SR scan. So
we need to walk the chain after the snapshot has been taken, not before.

This fixes the cause of the mentioned bug, but it doesn't help with
launching the partially corrupted snapshots created because of this bug,
so this only partially fixes the bug.

Change-Id: I0bf7535ae3f7d9e6820f8dc07075892953d80a78
Partial-Bug: #1362595

[{'created': '2014-09-18 13:36:43.000000000', 'message': "Upgrade PyScss to version 1.2.1 and pin it <1.3 for Horizon

PyScss fixed an important bug in parsing Bootstrap 3.2.0
(https://github.com/Kronuz/pyScss/issues/287). While investigating
this book with the upstream developers, we also became aware that
version 1.3 will break backwards compatibility with Django-PyScss
that we are using, so I'm pinning the version.

Change-Id: Ic4c23dcbf35dd55916401bba2b1bc3bf4baa4522
Partial-bug: #1370137

commit_message:
Upgrade PyScss to version 1.2.1 and pin it <1.3 for Horizon

PyScss fixed an important bug in parsing Bootstrap 3.2.0
(https://github.com/Kronuz/pyScss/issues/287). While investigating
this book with the upstream developers, we also became aware that
version 1.3 will break backwards compatibility with Django-PyScss
that we are using, so I'm pinning the version.

Change-Id: Ic4c23dcbf35dd55916401bba2b1bc3bf4baa4522
Partial-bug: #1370137

commit_message:
Upgrade/update instructions for 5.1; relnotes descriptions

This commit covers all the docs about upgrade and update
as well as refinements to the what-is, new-features, and
other-enhancements sections.

Includes change to use lrzuntar to unpack the 5.1 tarball
with a warning that the Fuel Master node requires 2GB RAM for
this to work, with a link to the hardware requirements for
the master

Includes corrections to the Release Notes Upgrade and Update sections
and to this information in the User Guide.

user-guide/cli.rst -- info from https://review.openstack.org/120428
about the update option.

Ref-Arch now includes 8000-fuel-upgrade that describes how
upgrade works

Release Notes are restructured to include:
- "Known Issues fixed in 5.1 and 5.0.2" is added in 117672
- "HA issues fixed in 5.1" is added in 117338

Change-Id: Ie2054b31ce216942fd64b5bf274d8efa7d300bc4
Closes-Bug: 1360372
Closes-Bug: 1367199

Logging features for Fuel and OpenStack

op-guide/troubleshooting -- using logs

terminology/logging -- brief overview of logging facilities with
links to our docs and community docs for additional information

commit_message:
Fix two functional tests within tempest_plugin

Couple of functional tests within tempest plugin are generic driver specific,
it verifies API actions of security-services, but for reproducing test cases
tries create shares and share creation fails if enabled backend driver raises
exception in case security-service has fake/improper data.

Change-Id: Ib8915f1f7d52a6abc2f34cac4bba18a6ad7eaf46
Closes-Bug: #1371552

Replaced unicode() with six.text_type()

According to https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Python3 unicode()
should be replaced with six.text_type().

commit_message:
Replace string format arguments with function parameters

There are files containing string format arguments inside
logging messages. Using logging function parameters should
be preferred.

Change-Id: I64a5ec9b640881b82b0165f067df49928b38e4ca
Partial-Bug: #1321274

Add support to build iso image

This script adds support to build iso image from the given
kernel and ramdisk

Implements: blueprint ilo-virtualmedia-ipa

commit_message:
Preserve environment variables when doing sudo

This commit adds the '-E' option for all the sudo commands
in build script of agent which causes it to preserve environment
variables.

Change-Id: Ic3fbc4ee8189cc82ef99359bf61eef33dae40a5a
Closes-Bug: 1371418

commit_message:
Fix dataflow work

 * We should send received task output as input context
   of next task, otherwise we can't get access to previous
   task output.

Change-Id: I18aa4c04d306faa15cd8ad72fc8f170de38df84c

commit_message:
Mark oslo.concurrency modules as obsolete

lockutils and processutils have moved to oslo.concurrency, so mark the
incubated versions as obsolete.

Change-Id: I51661492aad7204dcdeee8622e69d6b39212d289

commit_message:
Reuse API client object in a request

Previously API client object like novaclient are created
every time methods in openstack_dashboard/api.
It leads to regeneration of API HTTP connections.
This commit caches API client object for a WSGI request
to reduce the number of HTTP connection to backends.
As WSGI request object is recreated, a cached API client
object will live in a single request to Horizon.

Change-Id: I66620b3b0a2737c7232d91006e65d0fabbd3090b
Closes-Bug: #1352144

commit_message:
removed py3kcompat module

Like mentioned in I8e0b49cdfbddcf2d44a601ad06be2e75897905fc the
py3kcompat module is deprecated and should be removed.

Updated module apiclient from oslo-incubator to use six instead of
py3kcompat.

Change-Id: I79bea69077f64a2af23acd2326f52fd9ba6ddf59

commit_message:
Decrease squids cache max freshness time

Set the maximum time an object can be considered fresh to 1 day, 3 days
was a too aggressive considering a new package can be released, uploaded
to the openstack pypi mirror and set as a minimum requirement for a project in a shorter timeframe.

Closes-Bug: #1371549
Change-Id: If35d58de6a62bfc7ddd94d807c91c22fc8a09dda

Cindy, please see the following:

This is from python coding guideline. Even though underscore is allowed, by it is discouraged as indicated in the guideline. There is no benefit of making it monasca_api. In the project, you already have api package. thinking about that. monasca_api.api.something sounds really silly.

Package and Module Names

Modules should have short, all-lowercase names. Underscores can be used in the module name if it improves readability. Python packages should also have short, all-lowercase names, although the use of underscores is discouraged.

Since module names are mapped to file names, and some file systems are case insensitive and truncate long names, it is important that module names be chosen to be fairly short -- this won't be a problem on Unix, but it may be a problem when the code is transported to older Mac or Windows versions, or DOS.

When an extension module written in C or C++ has an accompanying Python module that provides a higher level (e.g. more object oriented) interface, the C/C++ module has a leading underscore (e.g. _socket)."}, {'account_id': 12133, 'date': '2014-09-15 20:53:51.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

Luckily our other separate modules have unique names so the install won't overwrite them.

You can keep it monasca.  If we decide to put the persister, and common code in this repo, then monasca does make sense.

Thanks"}, {'account_id': 2419, 'date': '2014-09-15 23:03:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

I've tested this, but the MetricValidator is never invoked. When POSTing a metric, the POST hits KafkaDispatcher.on_post_metrics and the validadator is not hit. My monasca.ini is the default one that was shipped as follows:

DEFAULT]
name = monasca

[pipeline:main]
# Add validator in the pipeline so the metrics messages can be validated.
pipeline = validator api

[app:api]
paste.app_factory = monasca.api.server:api_app

[filter:login]
use = egg: monasca_api#login

[filter:inspector]
use = egg: monasca_api#inspector

[filter:validator]
use = egg: monasca_api#metric_validator

[server:main]
use = egg:gunicorn#main
host = 0.0.0.0
port = 9090
workers = 1
proc_name = monasca"}, {'account_id': 2419, 'date': '2014-09-15 23:46:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

I've reviewed the code in monasca/middleware/metric_validator.py and understand that this is one of the "filters" that can be specified.

I'm just wondering how you see this working for all of the other REST endpoints defined in the Monasca API, such as statistics, measurements, alarms, notification-methods, ...

There is a big

        if (env.get('PATH_INFO', '').startswith('/v2.0/metrics') and
                env.get('REQUEST_METHOD', '') == 'POST'):

at the top of in the filter. So, I'm assuming that this filter is in the list of filters for all the REST endpoints in Monasca. The if block at the top basically tests to see if this is for a POST to the /v2.0/metrics endpoint. 

Are you thinking that there will be a "validator" class defined for each endpoint and that each implementation of that endpoint implements a if block at the top to filter it down?'}, {'account_id': 2860, 'date': '2014-09-16 01:17:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

Roland, glad that you see the point of doing it.
Now, say you have endpoint for /v2.0/events, you write a
similar middle ware to validate event messages. 
If both /v2.0/metrics and /v2.0/events are on the same
server, then you can chain the two filters.

like this:
pipeline = validator1 validator2 api

assume that validator1 is for metric validation and
validator2 is for event validation. Notice the ini file
has sections like this:

[filter:validator1]
use = egg: monasca_api#metric_validator

[filter:validator2]
use = egg: monasca_api#event_validator

each validator will only validate messages against a
particular endpoint. You probably already noticed the code
in MetricValidator.py which checks if the request is post
and the endpoint is /v2.0/metrics.

that is one way you can do this. Notice the server code
never changed.

the other way will be start another instance of this server at a different port, using a different config file. So the
server code is the same. Only configuration will be slightly different. Doing all this, it allows maximum code
reuse and very flexible setups.

Either you have one server serve both endpoints or two
servers serve each endpoint, that will be totally up to
you at CONFIGURATION time by simply editing the ini file.'}, {'account_id': 2419, 'date': '2014-09-16 02:48:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

Not sure you saw this earlier, but I had some problems getting the MetricsValidator invoked, but my monasca.ini file looks correct. See above. Any suggestions?

Not sure I buy into the point of doing things this way yet. One of my concerns is around performance. In the case that the MetricsValidator is one of the filters, when the validator is invoked it has to do a number of things:

1. First it gets invoked meaning that it is an extra filter within the list of filters. That adds the overhead of a function call. 
2. If I understand your comments, depending on how many filters there are, such as events and metrics validators, each validator is invoked, and each filter, must do a check on the endpoint, such as if "/v2.0/metrics" to test whether it should be used. So if we had an events and a metrics endpoint, there are two filters. But we have a lot more than two endpoints.
3. Most importantly, the validator reads the request, validates it, and then reformats it for the downstream kafka dispatcher. The kafka dispatcher on_post method then reads the message and write it to kafka. This data flow should be compared to the case of just invoking a single on_post method that does the validation and publishing to the Kafka queue. In that case the message is only read once. Is there a way to avoid reading the data twice. Seems like we are penalizing the case when input validation is done.

I haven't measured the impact of all the above yet, but I'm imagining there is one.

My other comment is that doing things like this in filters doesn't really seem like it was the intended use of filters and it is leading to a lot more complicated code. In the normal use of filters that I'm accustomed to a filter applies to cross-cutting concerns, like authentication, logging, auditing, performance analysis, ... I have no problems using filters for this.

However, when we start using filters for the main-line logic, and it is different logic for every endpoint it is going to lead to other problems, like the performance problems mentioned above, but also it is more complicated code. For sure the intended usage of Monasca seems like a second class citizen in this structure.

From an organizational view it seems a lot clearer to me to have a method called "on_post" in a class called "MetricResource". This is how the Falcon API examples are structured, such as http://falcon.readthedocs.org/en/latest/user/tutorial.html#first-steps. If we had a class called MetricResource with on_post the method looks like

def on_post(req, res):
    msg = read_request(req)

    if validation_enabled:
        is not is_valid(msg):
            return...

    parsed_metric = parse_metric(req)
    send_metric(parsed_metric)

To handle the case HP's or IBM's case one way to address that is to use the GOF Template Method pattern. Define a base class called MetricResource with methods read_request, is_valid and parse_metric, and then derive HpMetricResource and IbmMetricResource which implement those methods in the ways in which we each want them implemented.

For example, HP's implementation of is is_valid would actually do the validation of the request, and IBM's wouldn't. HP's implementation of parse_metric would return the metric in it's envelope for downstream processing, and IBM's would just return the request body that is passed in. send_metric would be the same in both cases.

it is also unclear what IBM is designing for if there are messages that are unathenticated, not validated, not using the same message formats, ...

Do we need to have a call on this. Maybe we should get the teams together to discuss further.'}, {'account_id': 2860, 'date': '2014-09-16 03:58:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

validators are used through out openstack pipelines. 
Authentication, ratelimits healthchecks are just few
examples. Some of the filters only use headers information,
some uses body (since you want to validate). If you follow
what I have proposed, you only read the body once before you
post to kafka. that is the minimum number of handling request
body if you want to validate, if you do it in filter or in
the app, it is your choice. But you have to read the body
at least once. Doing it in a filter makes the code small,
clean and it follows the design principal of "separation 
of concerns". 

For performance concerns, they are same. somewhere you have
to open up the body and read and parse it. Thinking about 
the path I described, it will only parse the body once.

For IBM use case, we will have cadf endpoint, and event
endpoint, which will take different format. and will also
have an datapoints endpoint which takes any data. I will
simply change the configurations with no parse whatsoever.

regarding the authentication, please look into the 
keystone authtoken filter, you simply need to add that
filter in your pipeline which monasca-api already defined
one. With that in the pipeline, your endpoint is secured
by keystone. Again, simple configuration, no code.

please do not make statements as you had in the previous
comments, sounds like IBM does not care authentication.
IBM cares a lot, just in a way that follows the design
patterns. not mixed that concern with other concerns.'}, {'account_id': 2419, 'date': '2014-09-16 05:18:51.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

My question regarding possible reasons why I can't get the metric validator invoked hasn't been addressed. Please seem my previous comments as I'm trying to test the code. Any suggestions on what is wrong?

I understand the use of validators in OpenStack. In all the examples you've provided I think they are a good use such as authentication, health-checks, rate-limits, ... I stated this in my previous post that I'm completely OK with validators in these case. These are cross-cutting concerns that are widely applicable to a broad number of methods.

The problem that I'm having is the use of validators for input validation and message formatting in the context that you are using it here. The input validation for a metric is not cross-cutting and broadly applicable. It applies to exactly one operation, POST /v2.0/metrics. It even does a test for the endpoint at the top. Similarly, this same logic would apply to event and any other endpoint. So, that seems like a pretty relevant difference from the examples of using auth, performance, rate-limiting, ..., for filters and a filter that only validates a metric request body and reformats it.

I completely realize you have to read the message at least once. My concern is that it looks like the combination of the metric validator and on_post method needs to read the message twice. Once in the metric validator in which it reads the message, parses it, and then stores the formatted message for the downstream processing. The other time for the on_post. Did I miss something? Is there a way to do this by only reading the message once. I was trying to run the code to validate this and analyze performance, but as I pointed out I didn't get the metric validator working. Looking at the code that seems to be what is being done. If that isn't the case then let me know. It just looks to me that there could be some extra over-head involved and I wanted to measure it. I don't want to penalize what I would consider to the the main-stream path for us. That path includes authentication, input validation, wrapping the metric in a envelope that include the tenant ID and some other info, and then sending to Kafka.

I also completely agree with the design right now for authentication and that this is done via the middleware and good separation of concerns. No problems in that area. That is exactly how we've done it in the Java implementation. Authentication is broadly applicable to a number of areas. 

Do you know of examples in OpenStack in which validators are being similar to how you are using them here?"}, {'account_id': 2860, 'date': '2014-09-16 13:08:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

Roland, yes, you missed it. if there are two validators,
the parse body will be done only once, NOT TWICE. metric
validator will parse the metric request body, the event
validator (for example) will only parse the event request
body. It can tell if a request is metric or event by
look at the endpoint, at that time, no parsing done. Only
taking information from request path, there is no parsing
body at that point. If you have a validator parsing 
every request body blindly, then you are not doing it right.

Regarding the validator not invoked, I think you may not installed it correctly, but even in that case, you should
see some errors such as validator middle ware can not
load or something like that. Should be easy to determine
once you turn on debug when you start gunicorn and in this
monasca.conf file.

add --debug --error-logfile err.log in the gunicorn
command line and also add the following line in
monasca.conf to turn on debug

default_log_levels = monasca=debug

This way, you should see some thing in err.log and whatever
the log file you defined in monasca.conf.

if you still can not get it going, let's have a call
sometime this afternoon."}, {'account_id': 2860, 'date': '2014-09-16 17:37:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

Roland, I am not aware anywhere in OS that we validate a request body. 

But this one from Swift is similar to what
the validator I created. Look at this file, 

swift/swift/common/middleware/formpost.py.

Take a look at that and it does a lot actually.

falcon also uses similar thing. see the request_helper.py.

Swift has a lot of use of the wsgi.input. Look into 
swift/common/middleware directory. you may find quite few
examples.'}, {'account_id': 12133, 'date': '2014-09-19 16:38:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 2419, 'date': '2014-09-19 16:41:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-19 16:41:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: -Verified

Build succeeded.

commit_message:
Remove running of one Heat test in system test 'Heat HA'

Heat OSTF 'test_autoscaling' is skipped in the HA mode, but in system tests
skipped test equal failed test, it is not correct in current situation. So need to don't
run test 'test_autoscaling' in the HA Heat system test.

Closes-Bug: #1371025

Change-Id: I5ab0495f4b57249ddce5de99512362f40d22aa2f

commit_message:
Support Cinder API version 2

This specification proposes to add support for the second version of the
Cinder API, which brings useful improvements and will soon replace
version one.

Change-Id: I7d03731167feffcd761056be28f96503918524ea

commit_message:
Don't clear _mounted_shares list in remoteFS while updating

This fix makes the updating of the _mounted_shares list in
remoteFS more of an atomic operation.  Previously this list
would be cleared, then rebuilt.  That allowed a race
condition where operations that took place during this
update would have a list of 0 shares to work with.

Closes-Bug: #1366083
cherry-picked from commit 9cc9cf111ef8a0265df5323fecaed12b0dabe312

commit_message:
Don't clear _mounted_shares list in remoteFS while updating

This fix makes the updating of the _mounted_shares list in
remoteFS more of an atomic operation.  Previously this list
would be cleared, then rebuilt.  That allowed a race
condition where operations that took place during this
update would have a list of 0 shares to work with.

Closes-Bug: #1366083
cherry-picked from commit 9cc9cf111ef8a0265df5323fecaed12b0dabe312
Change-Id: I740d8f1b87db911242326a38ff398b81c5974cea

Adds glossary to training guides

Glossary is added to training gudies. This glossary is in sync with
openstack manuals and should not be updated here. For any changes to
the glossary, please make them under openstack-manuals repository.
Glossary will be automatically updated from the openstack-manuals
repository.

commit_message:
Fix rootwrap for non openstack.org iqn's

The encryption methods implemented for attached volumes
require a symbolic link created to the /dev/disk-by* iqn.

The current implementation works fine for LVM, however the rootwrap
is restricted to only allow iqns of the form openstack.org, for
vendors that use their own target and iqn this won't work and will
result in the attach failing for unauthorized command.

This just makes the regex for the rootwrap filter a bit more
permissive, only looking for iscsi-iqn.*

Closes-Bug: 1362854
(cherry picked from commit 00808f2072c3ee8958ad16eabad7994730bb8b86)

Change-Id: I023ad24867c045a88f72c5ac7ac4e4da097a3643
Conflicts:
	etc/nova/rootwrap.d/compute.filters

Translation feedback - Add contextual marker for short strings

This commit add contextual markers to some short strings
which turned out difficult to distinguish during translations.

The detail descriptions are available in the bug report.
Closes-Bug: #1367104

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-08-19 12:16:27.000000000', 'message': "Avoid referencing stale instance/network_info dicts in firewall

This makes the virt.firewall code cleaner in terms of referencing
the cached instance and network_info code it stores. Before this
patch, concurrent instance operations could modify these two dicts
so that while we're iterating instances, the network_info dict
is suddenly missing information we need.

The right fix for this is to use instance objects and their
associated info_cache objects, but that's a larger fix and one
not as well-suited to backporting to previous releases which
suffer from this as well.

The approach taken here is that we store the instance and
network_info cache together in the same dict that we can pop()
from atomically (this is not really necessary, but helps to
prevent introducing more of these cases). When we iterate over
the contents, we iterate over a copy of the keys, being careful
not to let a suddenly-missing key break us, and passing the
details all the way down the stack instead of having deeper calls
hit the cache dicts again.

Conflicts:
	nova/virt/firewall.py

Change-Id: Ib1cfd68fca7789ca4a3602c25e6b8a956303fff9
Closes-bug: #1182131
(cherry picked from commit 72dd81343e73baf838bc58d413413f0d57018f15)
(cherry picked from commit 9f5d2a6a65edb2a5862c7f07b29ac700cec61f84)

commit_message:
Avoid referencing stale instance/network_info dicts in firewall

This makes the virt.firewall code cleaner in terms of referencing
the cached instance and network_info code it stores. Before this
patch, concurrent instance operations could modify these two dicts
so that while we're iterating instances, the network_info dict
is suddenly missing information we need.

The right fix for this is to use instance objects and their
associated info_cache objects, but that's a larger fix and one
not as well-suited to backporting to previous releases which
suffer from this as well.

The approach taken here is that we store the instance and
network_info cache together in the same dict that we can pop()
from atomically (this is not really necessary, but helps to
prevent introducing more of these cases). When we iterate over
the contents, we iterate over a copy of the keys, being careful
not to let a suddenly-missing key break us, and passing the
details all the way down the stack instead of having deeper calls
hit the cache dicts again.

Conflicts:
	nova/virt/firewall.py

Change-Id: Ib1cfd68fca7789ca4a3602c25e6b8a956303fff9
Closes-bug: #1182131
(cherry picked from commit 72dd81343e73baf838bc58d413413f0d57018f15)
(cherry picked from commit 9f5d2a6a65edb2a5862c7f07b29ac700cec61f84)

commit_message:
Allow to set protocol to 'ANY' on firewall rule update

Currently you can only update firewall rule protocol to TCP, UDP or
ICMP but ANY is also a valid protocol.

This change allows to update firewall rule protocol to ANY. In such
case we should send protocol == None to neutron because protocol ANY
means protocol == None in neutron context.

Closes-Bug: #1370485
Change-Id: I2a416f1ce2150fc5fcee06479f9578f688370e7e

commit_message:
Remove references to queue in Zaqar's description

Zaqar is a messaging service which provides support for different
messaging patterns and messaging related semantics. Mentioning `queue`
in the service codename and description misleads people from what the
service goal actually is.

Change-Id: I09df25e0bc9cf1804ea4db67271fb55d1dcce30d

fyi, the blueprint doesn't seem to exist?"}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2014-08-29 14:37:17.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

So, this whole thing remains slightly odd to me. pylockfile isn't used except in one oslo.db test that inherited from nova. We have our own locking library which is tested and used.

That being said, other people seem to be happy with that path, and are signing up for doing the work, so I'm +1 based on that. But it still seems like generating extra work in taking over another project when we have no shortage in front of us. :)"}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2014-08-29 15:59:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

The BP does exist: https://blueprints.launchpad.net/oslo-incubator/+spec/pylockfile-adoption

The hack we are using to link to blueprints by name (search in the openstack Launchpad projectgroup) fails now that we moved oslo projects under the oslo projectgroup). Oops.'}, {'account_id': 2271, 'date': '2014-09-01 23:02:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

There doesn't appear to be a rationale for _why_ we're doing this anywhere though. Am I missing it?"}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2014-09-02 16:30:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

@Michael - The spec describes the plan: http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack/oslo-specs/plain/specs/juno/pylockfile-adoption.rst'}, {'account_id': 2, 'date': '2014-09-06 18:46:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

Fine by me. I'm not crazy about:

"then release
oslo.lockutils as a thin-layer of top of it relying on oslo.config and
oslo.log."

It seems like if we can just make pylockfile do what we want, then I'd vote that we just don't have olso.lockutils at all.'}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2014-09-06 19:32:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@monty, possibly, although depending on the apis that we wish to introduce we likely can't just make it do what we want (since its a pre-existing library with pre-existing users), adding openstack specific dependencies and openstack specific apis into it will likely not be very nice to those existing users."}, {'account_id': 1561, 'date': '2014-09-08 15:10:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1'}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2014-09-09 17:49:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Here's our reasoning:

 The lockutils locking code is useful outside of OpenStack.
 The Oslo team wants to create libraries useful for non-OpenStack developers, when possible.
 The Oslo team should release lockutils.

 The Oslo team would prefer to contribute to existing projects rather than making new ones.
 pylockfile is an existing collection of variations on the theme of ‚Äúlocking files‚Äù.
 pylockfile would be a good home for the Oslo implementation of lockutils.

 The pylockfile maintainer is looking for someone to take over the library.
 The Oslo team wants to use pylockfile as a home for our lockfile module.
 The Oslo team has agreed to take over maintenance of pylockfile.

 There are existing OpenStack applications using lockfile.lock().
 The Oslo team does not want to break those applications by requiring them to change to a new API.
 The existing API for lockfile.lock() needs to be retained.

 The lockutils module uses a configuration option to set the lock path.
 The Oslo team does not want applications to define different forms of the same configuration option.
 The lockutils module should continue to define the configuration option.

 The lockutils module depends on oslo.config to create a configuration option to set the lock path.
 Libraries not in the ‚Äúoslo‚Äù branded namespace should not require oslo.config, to reduce dependency creep on non-OpenStack applications.
 The Oslo team can‚Äôt just move the public lock() API from lockutils to pylockfile."}, {'account_id': 2592, 'date': '2014-09-09 20:55:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 1, 'date': '2014-09-10 00:07:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 1561, 'date': '2014-09-16 21:01:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 1247, 'date': '2014-09-16 21:01:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 2271, 'date': '2014-09-16 21:01:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 2889, 'date': '2014-09-16 21:01:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-19 12:11:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Verified

subject: Graduate Zaqar (ex. Marconi) project
reviewers: [{'_account_id': 1, 'name': 'James E. Blair', 'email': 'jim@acmegating.com', 'username': 'corvus'}, {'_account_id': 2, 'name': 'Monty Taylor', 'email': 'mordred@inaugust.com', 'username': 'mordred'}, {'_account_id': 3, 'name': 'Jenkins', 'username': 'jenkins'}, {'_account_id': 7, 'name': 'Jay Pipes', 'email': 'jaypipes@gmail.com', 'username': 'jaypipes'}, {'_account_id': 67, 'name': 'Vish Ishaya', 'email': 'vishvananda@gmail.com', 'username': 'vishvananda'}, {'_account_id': 308, 'name': 'Thierry Carrez', 'email': 'thierry@openstack.org', 'username': 'ttx'}, {'_account_id': 964, 'name': 'Anne Gentle', 'email': 'annegentle@justwriteclick.com', 'username': 'annegentle'}, {'_account_id': 1247, 'name': 'Mark McLoughlin', 'email': 'markmc@redhat.com', 'username': 'markmc'}, {'_account_id': 1561, 'name': 'Russell Bryant', 'email': 'rbryant@redhat.com', 'username': 'russellb'}, {'_account_id': 1849, 'name': 'Joe Gordon', 'email': 'joe.gordon0@gmail.com', 'username': 'jogo'}, {'_account_id': 2271, 'name': 'Michael Still', 'email': 'mikal@stillhq.com', 'username': 'mikalstill'}, {'_account_id': 2472, 'name': 'Doug Hellmann', 'email': 'dhellmann@redhat.com', 'username': 'doug-hellmann'}, {'_account_id': 2592, 'name': 'Mark McClain', 'email': 'mark@mcclain.xyz', 'username': 'markmcclain'}, {'_account_id': 2750, 'name': 'Sean Dague', 'email': 'sean@dague.net', 'username': 'sdague'}, {'_account_id': 2889, 'name': 'Aeva Black', 'email': 'aeva.online@gmail.com', 'username': 'tenbrae'}, {'_account_id': 4257, 'name': 'Zane Bitter', 'email': 'zbitter@redhat.com', 'username': 'zaneb'}, {'_account_id': 6159, 'name': 'Flavio Percoco Premoli', 'email': 'fpercoco@redhat.com', 'username': 'flaper87'}, {'_account_id': 6413, 'name': 'Victoria Martinez de la Cruz', 'email': 'victoria@redhat.com', 'username': 'vkmc'}, {'_account_id': 6773, 'name': 'Lucas Alvares Gomes', 'email': 'lucasagomes@gmail.com', 'username': 'lucasagomes'}]

- noop http://logs.openstack.org/92/118592/2/check/noop/cd589a2 : SUCCESS'}, {'account_id': 2271, 'date': '2014-09-16 20:31:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 1, 'date': '2014-09-16 20:31:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

I don't think the TC and Zaqar are on the same page yet, but hope that we can make further progress in the next cycle."}, {'account_id': 2592, 'date': '2014-09-16 20:31:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1'}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2014-09-16 20:32:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1'}, {'account_id': 2, 'date': '2014-09-16 20:33:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1'}, {'account_id': 1561, 'date': '2014-09-16 20:33:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

I want Zaqar to succeed.  I think it's a valuable addition to OpenStack.  I think they've done a nice work working for a long time to get where they are.  The API is reasonably stable (as stable as other APIs are ...).

I also feel like the TC failed this cycle to provide real guidance if there were real concerns.  The "concerns" have mostly just turned out to be confusion from not looking at the project enough.

Ultimately, I also trust the team to continue to take feedback and iterate on it.'}, {'account_id': 1561, 'date': '2014-09-16 20:34:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

I should add that I would really like to see a more detailed write-up on what the gaps are from those on the -1 side of this.  The Zaqar team feels it's ready.  I think a -1 needs to come with "here are the gaps".'}, {'account_id': 1247, 'date': '2014-09-16 20:34:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

There's been a tonne of useful discussion about the scope, API and architecture, but I don't think any useful consensus direction from the project has emerged from the TC

i.e. there's no clear next steps for the project in Kilo if they don't graduate now, and no real sign of anyone to work closely with them to define it

The flip side of that is a project which fills an important use case, has traction, has a good community, works well with the community and is open to evolving in the future"}, {'account_id': 964, 'date': '2014-09-16 20:34:37.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

I think Zaqar has shown evidence of working well with the community and governance and can take on final work efforts next release, so I'm voting for graduation."}, {'account_id': 2889, 'date': '2014-09-16 20:34:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

I applaud the zaqar team's hard work, but find the recent and wide spread confusion about use cases (is it a queueing system? is it a message broker?) concerning.

For what it's worth, I think a messaging system is a valuable addition to the ecosystem, and have voted +1 on that change. I'd like to let the community digest this change in mission statements for a little while to determine if the current API, feature set, and performance meet their expectations for a messaging system -- I suspect the answer will be yes.

But I'm not comfortable with approving graduation until that consensus is reached."}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2014-09-16 20:42:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

+1000 Russell.

As someone who has been working on trying to clear up confusion and find consensus on the ML thread, it's *really* frustrating to see people who haven't been actively participating ask for another 6 months to talk about it, with no elaboration."}, {'account_id': 67, 'date': '2014-09-16 20:43:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2014-09-16 20:44:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

I feel like there are still too many open questions, and still two directions we can take. The blame is on the TC side for not having addressed those earlier, but the net result is the same. The first integrated cycle is a very busy one, and not the right time to reach such alignment. As such I feel we need to defer integration.'}, {'account_id': 6159, 'date': '2014-09-16 20:50:35.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

@ttx FWIW, The open questions is one of the things I'd like to get a detailed list for. It's really not clear to me, as of now, what those questions are, which is one of the things I wanted to discuss in the mailing list thread."}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2014-09-16 20:56:35.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

There's an obvious lack of consensus on this one. We need someone on the TC to be responsible for clarifying the discrepancies between what zaqar has built and what we think should have been built, if there are any."}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2014-09-16 20:57:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

@Flavio: We'd definitely need to provide a clear direction that we would be comfortable with. I'm still hesitating on my vote, to be honest. Deferring integration for something out of your control is a bit unfair."}, {'account_id': 6159, 'date': '2014-09-16 21:03:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

it does feel a bit unfair but regardless of that, it seems to me that, even though the team has clarified what the project aims to be, there are use cases for it and it seems to meet the requirements.'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2014-09-16 21:07:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Waiting on jaypipes vote, and checking if anybody switches their vote, before officializing'}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2014-09-16 23:00:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

I feel that Zaqar meets the conditions that have repeatedly been placed before it with regards to graduation reviews. I also feel that while it may not be everyone's cup of tea, it is undoubtedly a project that has valid use cases for tenants of cloud management platforms.

I agree that the TC (and the OpenStack community in general) need to resolve certain existential questions before proceeding any further on any incubation or graduation reviews, but I also find that it is neither fair to the Zaqar contributors nor promotes adoption of OpenStack and open cloud principles to continue to waffle on Zaqar's inclusion into the OpenStack family.

I vote +1.

-jay"}, {'account_id': 6413, 'date': '2014-09-17 12:55:27.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Do we need a cycle to agree on what Zaqar does? The project goals are clear and it covers several use cases as-is.

I don't think is fair for the team to have to postpone for another cycle, with all that means, just to put a name to the project objectives.

Zaqar has shown a good predisposition to respond to people concerns and to discuss changes on the API, and the team has also shown that it fits several use cases and that it has a stable API.

I'm positive that if graduation happens, the concerns claimed in the past meetings and in the ml will be cleared. And, if needed, we also have the summit soon to have a good and constructive discussion about it."}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2014-09-19 12:16:17.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

7 NO / 6 YES, final vote called on 20140916 meeting'}]

commit_message:
Resourcify the object stuff

Add some resource models to the swift stuff hopefully compatible
with future SDK type resource objects.  I wanted to add to the
object store capabilties, but it would be nice to have a pattern
that was similar to something that will be used in the future.

Change-Id: I611ecf842e452b7ff496fb5eac1d62f4291a61c1

commit_message:
Don't refresh network cache for instances building or deleting

Refreshing the network cache for an instance which is still building
is both unnecessary (the build itself will update the cache when it
completes) and can lead to a race condition if the periodic task gets
incomplete network information, then gets pre-empted by the build
thread, and then updates the cache after the build has finished.

Likewise there is no value in updating the network cache for an
instance which is in the process of being deleted.

Closes-Bug: 1254320
(cherry picked from commit 713e538237c7fea0b93ade343b1d9368bdbf2698)

Conflicts:
	nova/compute/manager.py

Change-Id: I7dd1d0a005662b979eaea3476af2506cbc51f17a

commit_message:
Mitigating performance impact with getting pci requests from DB

This change mitigates the performance impact in host manager that
retrieves an instance's PCI requests from DB while consuming it. This
is achieved by adding pci_requests into the instance dict before
calling consume_from_instance() and deleting it afterwards. The
complete solution will be provided when bug 1368260 is fully
addressed. The patch also removes the unnecessary context argument.

Change-Id: Ib0d12cde1c297a04e5d626b28d0a994c5dd4d965
Partial-Bug: 1368260

commit_message:
Added debug env to tox

A test can be run now in debug mode by running:
    tox -edebug <test_name>
e.g.
    tox -edebug test_create_table_duplicate

It is also possible to pass a regex so that you
don't run tests whose name contains the test_name
parameter. If you want just test_create_table to
run you can run just that test with:
    tox -edebug test_create_table$

Change-Id: If02cf5d9f5c44c67ac57689b83e3a2d6c42988fb

commit_message:
Removing obsolete reference to lesscpy

The settings file still contains a COMPRESS_PRECOMPILER reference
to lesscpy. With the transition to pyscss, this is no longer
necessary.

Closes-Bug: #1370823
Change-Id: I3baf70a631ef4560570c47d0982c8bc4ee3f8412

[{'created': '2014-09-13 06:36:29.000000000', 'message': 'Fix KeyError on missing gw_port_host for L3 agent in DVR mode

The order of Mixin imports broke the MRO, which caused some methods
in the L3 hierarchy to be ignored. In particular, _build_routers_list
for DVR was no longer called, which led to the stacktrace observed on
the L3 agent side.

Closes-bug: 1369012

Change-Id: I23cd9813fb9b67e9029d222d5f72733ecec3febb

commit_message:
Fix KeyError on missing gw_port_host for L3 agent in DVR mode

The order of Mixin imports broke the MRO, which caused some methods
in the L3 hierarchy to be ignored. In particular, _build_routers_list
for DVR was no longer called, which led to the stacktrace observed on
the L3 agent side.

Closes-bug: 1369012

Change-Id: I23cd9813fb9b67e9029d222d5f72733ecec3febb
