commit_message:
_from_db_object() to set the context to the RPC objects

Objects call _from_db_object() to transform a DB object into a RPC object
and before setting the context to the object was done after the object
has been formed, this patch is moving this bit to inside the function
resposable for the transformation.

Change-Id: I34ddfea130c6ec0d396e12e9a6b3aa221525bfc3
Partial-Bug: #1314732

commit_message:
Make the context parameter of create() mandatory on Objects

We want to make sure that every instantiation of RPC objects includes
the context. This patch is just a plumbing patch to help make that happen.

Change-Id: Ife9e0531fdf91080488df045134c264632ff21b8
Partial-Bug: #1314732

commit_message:
Add migration script to instance_info

The Nova Ironic Driver was changed to not get the deploy ramdisk and
deploy kernel from the Nova flavor anymore, it had to be done to enable
ironic to support different deploy provisioning methods using the same
flavor. This commit is adding a migration script that extracts the these
parameters from the flavor and add it to Nodes.

Implements: blueprint add-node-instance-info
Change-Id: I8799e5a6f3a81f6a8a14df6f69fede1e08d0679b

commit_message:
compute: tweaks to vm_mode APIs to align with arch/hvtype

Rename the 'name' method to 'canonicalize' to make its purpose
clearer. Also add a 'is_valid' method to check validity without
doing canonicalization. Make it use a specialized exception
class instead of the generic 'Invalid' class.

Related-bug: #1348629
Change-Id: I4bb972aeafb69be594bff40eded3cfeec22f0bef

[{'created': '2014-09-16 14:17:03.000000000', 'message': "Fix NUMA fit testing in claims and filter class

This patch makes sure that the overall topology is considered when
checking wather a NUMA instance can fit on a NUMA host, as previously we
would only check the corresponding cells without considering the overall
topology.

It adds a method for checking it on the VirtNUMAHostTopology class and
make sure it's called when checking for placement in the scheduler and
confirming claims on compute hosts.

We also split out the method for getting the topology from a host
as it can be reused in the scheduler now.

Change-Id: I038c81a5241bf1fd2ce37f7eff69f89ecedf59ef
Closes-bug: #1369984
"}]
commit_message:
Fix NUMA fit testing in claims and filter class

This patch makes sure that the overall topology is considered when
checking wather a NUMA instance can fit on a NUMA host, as previously we
would only check the corresponding cells without considering the overall
topology.

It adds a method for checking it on the VirtNUMAHostTopology class and
make sure it's called when checking for placement in the scheduler and
confirming claims on compute hosts.

We also split out the method for getting the topology from a host
as it can be reused in the scheduler now.

Change-Id: I038c81a5241bf1fd2ce37f7eff69f89ecedf59ef
Closes-bug: #1369984

[{'created': '2014-09-18 10:14:18.000000000', 'message': "VMware: Change disk type thick to lazyZeroedThick

The VMDK driver creates a lazyZeroedThick disk when the extra spec
value for vmware:vmdk_type is thick. The current documentation
uses the terminology 'thick' disk instead of 'lazyZeroedThick' disk.

Change-Id: Ie64d814578fbc0497b3c6afc378573ac3dfafb2a
Closes-Bug: #1371036
"}]
commit_message:
VMware: Change disk type thick to lazyZeroedThick

The VMDK driver creates a lazyZeroedThick disk when the extra spec
value for vmware:vmdk_type is thick. The current documentation
uses the terminology 'thick' disk instead of 'lazyZeroedThick' disk.

Change-Id: Ie64d814578fbc0497b3c6afc378573ac3dfafb2a
Closes-Bug: #1371036

commit_message:
Extract logs from syslog to logs archive

We moved the logs for individual services from the upstart directory to
syslog, In order to keep the timestamps consistent. Now extract them back
out of syslog in order make them available to be indexed in logstash.

Change-Id: I27ea3d465670277ef1ddf3d1b3b9d52df4162807

Separation of different actions in single procedure

Separate one procedure into three new sections:

*View the Block Storage quotas
*Edit and update the Block Storage quotas

commit_message:
Replace calls to Mock.assert_not_called

Mock.assert_not_called() isn't a valid mock method. This replaces
those calls with self.assertFalse(<mocked-obj>.called).

It also fixes one of the tests that was incorrectly (trying to) assert
using the wrong mock object.

Change-Id: Ieecf23de335b15df5811d57ecf9ddd3a30919fa2
Closes-Bug: #1370583

commit_message:
Remove explicit dependency on amqplib

kombu already depends on amqp or amqplib depending on its
version, and no explicit access to amqplib exists in neutron code.

Conflicts:
	requirements.txt

Closes-Bug: #1317094
Change-Id: I5cf189d7173b732cba6df3f9b6aff1d2bb85cdfe
(cherry picked from commit 39ffcb0dd75d9dc5d8a249f2974a67f0def5204b)

commit_message:
Remove running of one Heat test in system test 'Heat HA'

Heat OSTF 'test_autoscaling' is skipped in the HA mode, but in system tests
skipped test equal failed test, it is not correct in current situation. So need to don't
run test 'test_autoscaling' in the HA Heat system test.

Closes-Bug: #1371025

Change-Id: I5ab0495f4b57249ddce5de99512362f40d22aa2f

commit_message:
Select AuthProvider type from credentials type

auth_version is used to get defaul credentials as well as to
select the AuthProvider class. If credentials of an API version
different from the configured one are used, a mismatch happens.

Instantiating the AuthProvider class that corresponds to the
version of API represented by the credentials object.

Closes-Bug: #1369557

Change-Id: I1ed6da90ce0abed805cf39190cb1ac3baa3f63b6

commit_message:
rephrase action_past text in Access & Security panel

Convention in Horizon seems to be verb first, e.g "Deleted
Key Pair."  Also fix capitalization.

commit_message:
Return current user/project for user/project show commands

If non-admin user attempts 'project show' or 'user show' on the currently
authenticated project or user return the information that is already in the
service catalog rather than throwing a Forbidden error.

Change-Id: Ieeb6eacf71a471e410fbd3c09e7871740547e890

commit_message:
Sync the doc with latest code

Our agent_ipmitool, agent_ilo, iscsi_ilo, pxe_ilo and agent_pyghmi
drivers also support sending notifications to Ceilometer. However,
in our install-guide.rst, we just mentioned pxe_ipmitool and
pxe_ipminative drivers, so the documentation needs to be synced with
current code.

Change-Id: Ic6dec44ba11177d0a350c5b4e3cf1eae3658c1b7
Closes-Bug: #1369838

commit_message:
Adds storwize_svc_npiv_compatibility_mode flag to Storwize/SVC driver

This configuration option allows the driver to function in an
environment where an attach operation occurs before the virtual FC
ports are logged into the fabric.

Today's behaviour (which is maintained as default behaviour) is to
only build the initiator_target_map for initiator ports that are
logged into the fabric, and error if there are no such ports.

If this new flag is set to True, then if no initiator ports are
found on the fabric, ALL initiator ports are placed into the
initiator_target_map, rather than none, which is the case today.

Closes-Bug: 1346622
Change-Id: Ie722612bc5a9af2816348392c0c39da003b99028

commit_message:
virt: use compute.virttype constants and validate virt type

Where we have hardcoded hypervisor types, use compute.hvtype
constants. Where we get hypervisor types from external systems,
validate them against the list of acceptable names.

The Xen hypervisor is reporting a virt type of 'xapi' for
supported instances which is confusing the virtualization
type with the hypervisor API access method. It should be
reporting 'xen' as the virtualization type.

On the other side, the ImagePropertiesFilter will canonicalize
the hvtype it fetches from image metadata, so that 'xapi' gets
remapped to 'xen' during comparison.

Upgrade-impact: the hyervisor type will intentionally no longer
  distinguish libvirt Xen from XenAPI within a compute cloud.
  The driver name should be used instead
Closes-bug: #1348623
Change-Id: I2c740e8eb068a5d93ba5f72292fb30d899931ea5

commit_message:
Standardize on the same lock acquire method definition

It appears the the other drivers have a acquire that does not
take a timeout, but the zookeeper driver has a acquire method that
does take a timeout.

To be more consistent just standardize on the acquire not taking
a timeout paramater and having it provided by the driver options
like the IPC and memcached drivers do.

Change-Id: I86d5197ad57a4c891615e100365347e3e0bdd4c3

commit_message:
Standardize on hiding the lock implementation

It seems like the other drivers (if they use a proxy object
to do the locking) hide the lock in the external non-proxy
object so this changes mirrors that hiding of the proxy object
instead of exposing it.

Change-Id: I2bd8f8c9f66aed960d14784053b9b32999ac394e

Hi Ling-Yun,

Here are some writing suggestions that may address Christian's initial comment on "improving the overall text" I am not very familiar with the technical aspects here, so please correct any errors I may have inadvertently introduced.

Just some ideas!

Thanks,

Laurel

***


When you create new volumes, the Block Storage service can choose a volume backend based on free_capacity and allocated_capacicty. You can improve IO balance and performance by telling the scheduler to consider the total number of available backends when assigning volumes to backends. You do this by usinig the VolumeNumberWeigher setting.

To enable the VolumeNumberWeigher setting, edit the cinder.conf file to include this line:

scheduler_default_weighers=VolumeNumberWeigher

This flag sets VolumeNumberWeigher as the the selected weigher.

Note

VolumeNumberWeighter can not replace CapacityWeigher and AllocatedCapacityWeigher. These weighers balance the free storage space on volume backends, and may be appropriate when a user is more concerned with free space balance than IO.'}, {'account_id': 8874, 'date': '2014-08-15 00:24:50.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-15 00:24:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

commit_message:
Configure and use volume number weigher

Cinder volume number weigher(https://review.openstack.org/#/c/102414/) has
been merged into cinder.
It needs add docs for how to configure and use volume number weigher.

Change-Id: I1dcf2424b8ce7cf349c88103484901fe3db5d16f
Closes-Bug: #1338456

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-09-16 12:21:32.000000000', 'message': 'Allow pecan debug middleware to be turned off

The Pecan DebugMiddleware is turned on or off based on the
ceilometer.conf-wide debug setting. This is not useful for situations
where running ceilometer-api under mod_wsgi with multiple processes
is desired.

This change adds a pecan_debug setting to the api section of config,
defaulting to the DEFAULT debug value. mod_wsgi install docs updated
accordingly.

Configuration docs have not yet been udpated. They will be pending a
fix to bug: #1370030

Closes-Bug: #1370009

Change-Id: Ib4a472e3c8d1f34f64a5f3ab993c1211dee8af9a
'}, {'created': '2014-09-16 15:01:17.000000000', 'message': 'Allow pecan debug middleware to be turned off

commit_message:
Allow pecan debug middleware to be turned off

The Pecan DebugMiddleware is turned on or off based on the
ceilometer.conf-wide debug setting. This is not useful for situations
where running ceilometer-api under mod_wsgi with multiple processes
is desired.

This change adds a pecan_debug setting to the api section of config,
defaulting to the DEFAULT debug value. mod_wsgi install docs updated
accordingly.

Configuration docs have not yet been udpated. They will be pending a
fix to bug 1370030

Closes-Bug: #1370009

Change-Id: Ib4a472e3c8d1f34f64a5f3ab993c1211dee8af9a

Backport in oslo-incubator: 4cf1a2a158f7c3c21799bf2e6ba0e7b5fbc25d62

commit_message:
Sync latest process and str utils from oslo

This backport the necessary changes to fix both issues:
* Make execute method clean password in exception
* Make sure mask_password works properly

Backport in oslo-incubator: 4cf1a2a158f7c3c21799bf2e6ba0e7b5fbc25d62

Closes-Bug: 1343604
Closes-Bug: 1345233
SecurityImpact

Change-Id: I3b49b1d667f6ade9ae3f6765d735440a3e838917

commit_message:
Add support for 'file' format objects

Some objects can be saved as 'dirname/filename' which causes the
existing support to fail. The correct behaviour should be to
create the directories needed.

Change-Id: I71c61bc3b0f76a3e6d2703bd45508f9d6483546e

Switch heat engine to oslo.i18n

Remove gettextutils from heat engine and import oslo.i18n.

blueprint oslo-i18n

commit_message:
Add user data and config drive properties

Added these missing properties and upgraded the client
library requirements to support them. This upgrade breaks
Swift compatability, but we don't need to override that
client any more anyway, so client registration for
Swift-via-pyrax is also removed.

Change-Id: I8e07092adf58da2a39330789fb170986176f47e3
Closes-Bug: 1336498

- gate-tempest-dsvm-ceilometer-mongodb-full http://logs.openstack.org/04/121104/3/check/gate-tempest-dsvm-ceilometer-mongodb-full/b8f7945 : SUCCESS in 45m 10s (non-voting)'}, {'account_id': 7052, 'date': '2014-09-15 14:42:49.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

Nejc, I understand the benefits from a performance perspective because now you can move the polling of one endpoint across several central agents subdividing it by tenants.
My concern here is troubleshooting. Before it was fairly easy to troubleshoot issues because there will be a lack of meters corresponding to a particular service but now you will need to see which tenants you got the data and which you didn't which is hard.
This seems to me to be a corner case anyway, so my concern is that we give people a level of granularity that (if misused) they will regret ... 
Please tell me if I am on the wrong path here ..."}, {'account_id': 8052, 'date': '2014-09-15 14:56:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

You have valid concerns Fabio. There are debug logs logging which resources/tenants/... a particular agent is polling (https://github.com/openstack/ceilometer/blob/master/ceilometer/coordination.py#L139). All a user has to do is check out all the central agents' logs and see which one is spewing errors.

Dina & Igor tested fine-grained partitioning of the compute agent in multinode environment, and it worked great."}, {'account_id': 7052, 'date': '2014-09-15 15:01:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Nejc, ok but the issue is that in prod you don't have your logs set in debug mode. :-)
Would it be possible to partition based on Domain (or as it would be in the future called root project), in this way you have a compromise between granularity and easiness to debug since you could report that your are polling for domain X in the info log and then I can easily find all the tenants in that domain and identify if the pollster has missed something..."}, {'account_id': 8052, 'date': '2014-09-15 15:14:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

It's true there are no debug logs, but there are WARNING and ERROR logs. If something's wrong, there should be warnings/errors in the offending agent. Are we doing ourselves a favour by not doing workload-partitioning at all? (which is the case with partitioning endpoints, I don't know what domains are though) In that case we could just run agents in active/passive mode."}, {'account_id': 7052, 'date': '2014-09-15 15:18:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Ok, but hang on a sec. You are partitioning by service and by region already and in NORMAL environment this is the rule.
The case you trying to solve here is a corner case where in a specific env. there is only 1 instance on swift in 1 region and the central agent that takes it has a lot more work. This seems to me a bad deployment strategy rather than a real issue to solve.'}, {'account_id': 8052, 'date': '2014-09-16 07:03:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Currently, Ceilometer has almost non-existent support for multi-service. Perhaps this should change in the future (I don't know if it's a common deployment strategy to have multiple Swift endpoints in a single region?), but currently, most pollsters simply instantiate their service's client without regard for the possibility of there being multiple endpoints in that region.

So what you say is a corner case is actually the most common case (and the only one that was supported for Swift at all): 1 service in 1 region. Partitioning the set of endpoints is just a 'hack' to get some partitioning at all, which happens to support multi-service as well, but that was not the main purpose of it.

The intent behind the workload-partitioning patches was to distribute the workload as evenly as possible, which means preferring fine-grained resources. We went down that route and this patch is in line with that spirit."}, {'account_id': 3012, 'date': '2014-09-17 11:39:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1

Fabio, ok, I got your concerns. Actually I suppose that might be a separated change, but anyway - what do you propose to do now in Nejc's change? For me his change looks quite consistent, and the problem you described seems needs to be solved globally I guess"}, {'account_id': 7052, 'date': '2014-09-17 14:46:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1

Ok. Maybe we should discuss these kind of stuff at the summit and have a long term plan.
Thanks.'}, {'account_id': 4491, 'date': '2014-09-18 03:16:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-18 03:16:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: -Verified

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-09-12 13:08:49.000000000', 'message': "Partition swift pollster resources by tenant

Since the latest discovery change, Swift pollsters on different
agents only decide which who should poll. Most of the time there's
only one endpoint, so only one agent gets to do any work.

This patch fixes this by introducing a new TenantDiscovery, which
enables Swift (and other in the future) pollsters to partition the
set of keystone tenants among them and then each poll the samples
for their assigned subset of tenants.

Closes-Bug: #1365351
Change-Id: Iba4a3b91d5ee978213fdd6fcf8bb62b315324a52
"}, {'created': '2014-09-15 10:53:20.000000000', 'message': "Partition swift pollster resources by tenant

commit_message:
Partition swift pollster resources by tenant

Since the latest discovery change, Swift pollsters on different
agents only decide which who should poll. Most of the time there's
only one endpoint, so only one agent gets to do any work.

This patch fixes this by introducing a new TenantDiscovery, which
enables Swift (and other in the future) pollsters to partition the
set of keystone tenants among them and then each poll the samples
for their assigned subset of tenants.

Closes-Bug: #1365351
Change-Id: Iba4a3b91d5ee978213fdd6fcf8bb62b315324a52

commit_message:
Fix sample files miss for os-aggregates

There are some sample files for os-aggregates V3 API assigning
'deleted' element with '0', which should be assigned to 'false'.
This patch fixes it.

Change-Id: I6d7814ce98bc0c701d4eabefcbe64100345cb2d3
Closes-Bug: #1294556

messages:

If we change from 'data store' to 'datastore' we should change it everywhere. At the moment I'm not sure about the wording. I think 'data store' is correct, isn't it?"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-17 12:32:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

VMware documentation and products such as vSphere client (vCenter client) uses the terminology datastore.

Please see:
http://pubs.vmware.com/vsphere-55/index.jsp?topic=%2Fcom.vmware.vsphere.storage.doc%2FGUID-057D6054-0A51-4023-B90A-D737DB0426F4.html


This patch replaces all the occurrence in VMDK driver config reference because the bug is created for that page. We can have separate patches for Nova and Glance.'}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2014-09-17 16:19:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-2

We use our own conventions and in cases as this follow the IBM list:

http://www-01.ibm.com/software/globalization/terminology/d.html'}, {'account_id': 964, 'date': '2014-09-17 16:23:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-2

Thanks Vipin for working on this. 

We need consistency and have a lot of time and effort into agreeing to the IBM Style Guide, as you can imagine that is no small feat. 

I think the best course would be for you to note that VMWare uses "datastore" but that the OpenStack documents use the generic "data store" term throughout, and that this document will use "data store" throughout.'}, {'account_id': 9171, 'date': '2014-09-18 06:57:46.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
VMware: Replace 'data store' with 'datastore'

This patch replaces 'data store' with 'datastore' in VMware VMDK driver
config reference in order to be consistent with VMware terminology.

Change-Id: I8ba8d8291db29411f59b3b99bc2661fd7f921c6a
Closes-Bug: #1370475

[{'created': '2014-09-12 20:41:06.000000000', 'message': "Stop using intersphinx

Remove intersphinx from the docs build as it triggers network calls that
occasionally fail, and we don't really use intersphinx (links other
sphinx documents out on the internet)

This also removes the requirement for internet access during docs build.

This causes docs jobs to fail because we error out on warnings.

Change-Id: I71e941e2a639641a662a163c682eb86d51de42fb
Related-Bug: #1368910
"}]
commit_message:
Stop using intersphinx

Remove intersphinx from the docs build as it triggers network calls that
occasionally fail, and we don't really use intersphinx (links other
sphinx documents out on the internet)

This also removes the requirement for internet access during docs build.

This causes docs jobs to fail because we error out on warnings.

Change-Id: I71e941e2a639641a662a163c682eb86d51de42fb
Related-Bug: #1368910

commit_message:
Validate display_name for volumes and snapshots

Currently, when create or edit volume or snapshot, it allows name
field with only white spaces. This patch add check for display_name
when creating or updating volume and snapshot.

Change-Id: Iae0b8855a5c521d8dfc0596692621ec55c177242
Closes-bug: #1370297

commit_message:
Deprecate Role and ImageBuilder metadata handling

Our templates and elements no longer depend on `OpenStack::Role` or
`OpenStack::ImageBuilder::Elements` metadata. Using either now prints out a
deprecation warning.

Change-Id: I91e79b00bacca8caf13d4b6fa83d90e9c20b241c

It sounds like this is building in some of those smarts to rebalance, which sounds reasonable I think - assuming that's basically what's going on?

Either way, it stinks to have it as a positional argument - add devices already does this trick where the options can come in as flags instead of the dsl - can you do something with this command to make it support optparse options as well as the positional arguments to get rid of the (clunky?) I think there's two issues that we need to think about:

1) Setting the number of parts to move at a *time* doesn't fix the issue that eventually balance will ignore weight and move all the parts to fit unique-as-possible (by "design"?).  Currently, you can have a ring that will *NOT* balance, no matter how long you take to get there.

2) If you fail some devices you may need to move more parts than on the command line option - I think we need to handle these failed devices better.  That can mean either:

    a) taking failed parts first, possibly more than the limit
    b) make a limit of parts that can change server/zone/region - rather than a limit on parts that can *move*.

If you can think of a way to punt on #1 that's fine - it's an existing "problem" - albeit, IMHO, the root cause that prompted this change.  But not fixing #2 doesn't yet seem reasonable to me (open to discussion) because this limit option gives operators a great tool for shooting themselves in the foot when faced with failed devices (sam caught this, BTW).

Honestly, if we can solve #1 I think we get #2 for free because you can gradually increase weight in the remote region which limits the number of parts that can move there per rebalance without changing the total number of parts that need to be reassigned because of failures or unique-as-possible (I think?).

Here's a couple of test cases to think about:

https://gist.github.com/clayg/332e2d466637c9013ffb

Thoughts?'}, {'account_id': 8871, 'date': '2014-07-10 19:08:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

For bug details see: http://status.openstack.org/elastic-recheck/'}, {'account_id': 6968, 'date': '2014-07-11 09:00:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Workflow-1

@Clay: i fully agree with you.

1) looks to me like it is by design, handling each zone and region independently.
This might have some drawback if you're using regions and zones that are sized very differently and might create much more partitions on each disk in smaller regions/zones. You need to think about the biggest and smallest regions at the same time and try to balance everything when setting the initial partition power.

Actually rebalancing enforces distribution across zones and regions: https://github.com/openstack/swift/blob/master/swift/common/ring/builder.py#L643 When adding a new zone or region the other zones and regions get a lower value here, thus partitions need to move, and this results in ignoring the weight (well, not really ignoring it - it is taken into account inside each zone and region, but not globally).

I tried another approach, but that one has a new drawback and needs some more work to get it right. It basically add's a switch to disable enforcing partition spread across more than two devices: https://gist.github.com/cschwede/0745b042ef34a6f759b9

Probably a blueprint/spec makes sense now..."}, {'account_id': 6968, 'date': '2014-08-22 06:16:25.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

Abandoning this patch; https://review.openstack.org/#/c/115441/ is approved and that patch is a huge improvement adding much more flexibility when scaling up or down. No need for this one.'}, {'account_id': 6968, 'date': '2014-09-12 13:33:04.000000000', 'content': "Restored

Looks like we still need this; I'll upload a new review with a link to a new bug report."}, {'account_id': 6968, 'date': '2014-09-12 13:34:52.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 6968, 'date': '2014-09-12 13:44:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

@Clay: I reopened and modified this patch, and included a good part of your tests from the gist - thanks for that!

So, unfortunately when adding a new region or zone to an existing cluster there is still a lot of partition movement inside the existing region; most of the time it is between 50% and 100% of the partitions.

Have a look at the difference: https://gist.github.com/cschwede/c17fa09bfa83411da2e3

I was also thinking to limit the maximum number of selected partitions automatically to 10%, and increasing this by 10% for every loop in https://github.com/openstack/swift/blob/master/swift/common/ring/builder.py#L351-L361.'}, {'account_id': 6968, 'date': '2014-09-12 14:13:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

To shed some more light what happens currently: when adding a new region or zone (even with a total weight of 0.0), the max_allowed_replicas per tier is lowered (https://github.com/openstack/swift/blob/master/swift/common/ring/builder.py#L654) and the ringbuilder adds these partitions to the list of partitions to reassign. I tried several other modifications to this code, but none was passing all the current tests.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-12 15:31:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Verified+1

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-07-09 07:49:08.000000000', 'message': 'Limit changed partitions when rebalancing

When adding new regions or zones to an existing, already balanced
ring it is very likely that 100% of the partitions will be rebalanced
at once. This will create a lot of replication traffic in the backend
network and might have a performance impact.

This patch adds a new option to the rebalance command to limit the
number of partitions that will be reassigned. This is done by limiting
the number of partitions that are choosen for a reassignment.
The existing behavior and command line options are not modified; because
of the fact that the rebalance command already uses a positional
argument <seed> you need to set this too. To rebalance the whole ring one
can execute the rebalance multiple times. The following example limits
the number of reassigned partitions to 100 (and ignores the initial
value for the seed argument):

    swift-ring-builder object.builder rebalance None 100
    swift-ring-builder object.builder rebalance None 100
    swift-ring-builder object.builder rebalance None 100

A unit test has been added to ensure the correct behavior when adding
a new region to an existing, already balanced ring.

Also-By: Florent Flament <florent.flament-ext@cloudwatt.com>
Change-Id: I36e4bb69c9238d44b861e1cd05a26977a9852140

commit_message:
Limit changed partitions when rebalancing

When adding new regions or zones to an existing, already balanced
ring it is very likely that 100% of the partitions will be rebalanced
at once. This will create a lot of replication traffic in the backend
network and might have a performance impact.

This patch adds a new option to the rebalance command to limit the
number of partitions that will be reassigned. This is done by limiting
the number of partitions that are choosen for a reassignment.

Failed devices are not considered when applying the limit, thus a
rebalance with a limit might actual change more partitions if required.

The existing behavior and command line options are not modified. To
rebalance the whole ring one can execute the rebalance multiple times.
The following example limits the number of reassigned partitions to 100
(and ignores the initial value for the seed argument):

    swift-ring-builder object.builder rebalance --reassign-max 100

Two unit tests have been added to ensure the correct behavior when adding
a new region to an existing, already balanced ring and dealing correctly
with failed devices.

Closes-Bug: 1367826
Also-By: Florent Flament <florent.flament-ext@cloudwatt.com>
Change-Id: I36e4bb69c9238d44b861e1cd05a26977a9852140

commit_message:
Update doc for qos_policy_group NetApp extra spec

Bug 1288283 updated the function behind the qos_policy_group extra spec,
but the docs were never updated to reflect the change in behavior from
being a capability advertised to the scheduler to being a directive that
needed to be executed post provisioning.

Change-Id: Ia91a7cde1e0c9343de682d7b30a9898c6319ae8b

commit_message:
Update database content for Juno

I updated database content in the installation guide for Juno
as follows:

1) Changed Ubuntu, RHEL, CentOS, Fedora, and OpenSUSE to use
   MariaDB. Debian and SLES continue to use MySQL.
2) Adjusted wording to remove dependencies on specific database
   servers.
3) Implemented changes from the improvements blueprint including
   procedure structure and note about PostgreSQL.

Change-Id: I8608e2329d87b237a259f366976e8ec1b7f50bdc
Implements: blueprint installation-guide-improvements

Remove direct dep on oslo-incubator jsonutils

It is used by the log and wsgi and therefore cannot be entirely
removed

commit_message:
Set allow_migrate_to_same_host as True by default

After OpenStack was installed with devstack on a single node, cold
migration always failed because the default value of
allow_migrate_to_same_host is False. This means that devstack do not
support cold migrate a VM to a same host by default.

Normally, a developer will set up OpenStack with devstack on a single
node, so it is better that we change this value to True to enable
cold migration with a single node after installed by devstack.

Change-Id: I961395f1c79d9600917b6186964c13c92a8a6266

commit_message:
Switch config to use Ironic driver from Nova's tree

Change the Nova config to use the IronicDriver from the Nova tree,
so that the copy of this driver in Ironic's tree may be deleted.

Also removes the unneeded [ironic] "sql_connection" config parameter
which was cruft copied from the nova_bm configuration in commit
06fb29c66124b6c753fdd262eb262043b4551298

Change-Id: I35473b54d760bfa7395decbe6b086f64db60ab10

[{'created': '2014-09-15 09:28:08.000000000', 'message': "neutron: use non-deprecated notification_driver

Neutron is now using oslo.messaging so it should be
using 'messaging' as its notification driver and not the now deprecated
full python path to the oslo-incubator notification driver.

Change-Id: Ie4a4020e59473473ad62059c66507f5b73b93375
"}]
commit_message:
neutron: use non-deprecated notification_driver

Neutron is now using oslo.messaging so it should be
using 'messaging' as its notification driver and not the now deprecated
full python path to the oslo-incubator notification driver.

Change-Id: Ie4a4020e59473473ad62059c66507f5b73b93375

commit_message:
Add RBD as a known store

Adding RBD as a known store in the glance-api.conf file allows us to use
Ceph as a backend for Glance.

Closes-Bug: 1369578

Change-Id: I02cbafa68ca3293cedc9fef7535e79930cc4ee5c
Signed-off-by: S√©bastien Han <sebastien.han@enovance.com>

commit_message:
User-specified undercloud and overcloud img names

The names of locally built or cached images is currently hard-coded,
making it awkward to manage multiple sets of pre-built images during
upgrades or downgrades.  This allows the name of undercloud and
overcloud images to be user-specified as environment variables while
preserving existing behavior via defaults.

Change-Id: I39d5e20dd090804984e0dc723deb4f11f81ef950

Hi Terry, 
Thanks for your review. How about performance issues when it tries uploading an entire huge chunk even after the token has expired. Doesn't fail fast-refetch token-retry  sound better?"}, {'account_id': 7701, 'date': '2014-04-03 07:05:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Also we're reusing the same connection."}, {'account_id': 8736, 'date': '2014-04-03 14:39:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

You are trying to solve a session layer problem at the application layer.  In the case of keystone, the token comes with an expiration time.  It would make a lot more sense to make a session layer check  to see if the token is expired and automatically get a new one if it has.  This would all happen and the application would never even see it.'}, {'account_id': 917, 'date': '2014-04-03 14:55:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Just adding some thoughts.

1.  It is still possible for the token to be invalidated between the head and the next request.
2.  I agree that it is a lot of overhead to do a HEAD before each request just to check auth
3.  Tokens can, and in practice do get revoked before their time is up, and thus checking the ttl on the token can also be problematic.
 
I think the right solution here is to add expect: 100-continue support to requests.  It will never get added if everyone just waits around for it."}, {'account_id': 7701, 'date': '2014-04-07 07:01:16.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Hi,

I think that the possibility of the token expiring in between the HEAD and PUT calls is a 1 in million case. But not altogether impossible. 

I agree that the additional HEAD call before each putrequest looks dirty, but honestly it wont be too much of a performance crunch as we're reusing the same connection here. Also changing the ttl on the token is not an option. 

'100-continue' would be the ideal candidate here but as per https://github.com/kennethreitz/requests/issues/713, they do not find it relevant at the moment and I do not see it go in anytime soon. May be we could push a little for it at the discussion. but it didn't help me much."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-04-07 07:01:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: No score

commit_message:
swiftclient should check response before upload

Scenario:

1. swiftclient receives a request to upload an image
2. swiftclient obtains an auth token
3. upload of the image commences are multiple chunks.
4. mid way the orignal auth token expires.
5. swiftclient attempts to upload the next chunk with the same auth token
6. Upload fails with a 401 after attempting to upload the entire chunk.

Proposed solution:

1. Fire a HEAD call before the actual PUT call with the same headers.
2. If the status returned is a 401, refetch the auth token and retry.
3. Upload the remaining chunks with the new token.

Fixes bug #1298283
Change-Id: I6f2d4c6bc883a632ff71ca2f6176012a8f0128d0

interface for updating object info in a container DB. Each object has

commit_message:
isolate object update logic from container PUT

To further extend pluggble container backends we need to have better
interface for updating object info in a container DB. Each object has
`name`, `timestamp` and metadata, the metadata is taken from the request
headers, usually.

The new `object_update()` method allows us to isolate metadata extraction.
We can push more logic there if backend supports smarter PUTs (more
metadata, for example).

Change-Id: I1aae3e73a56c3800ccd7a8d4f818c518b5118bb1

commit_message:
The python-qpid packages must be installed when qpidd is configured

The python-qpid package is available for Ubuntu trusty, precise, and
all the supported RHEL based platforms.  This package is necessary if
qpidd is configured as the RPC backend.  It is the client API used to
talk to the broker, and must be installed on each system that
communicates with the broker.

Change-Id: I635d3e857aa4b769a80cb7cde405cfd6cae44d32

 * direct_put_object
 * direct_post_object

But it's already in Swift and people may find it useful for their needs and their use cases, even there is not a concrete use case that we aware.
May be it's a good point to have all APIs in direct client, like those proposed in this patch, otherwise - it's a direct client, that somewhere in the middle. Or it should be removed or enriched with missing APIs that people may be find useful.

commit_message:
Sendfile acceleration for GET requests

This is a bit of a hack that only works if you're using the eventlet's WSGI
server and nothing has changed too dramatically in various private interfaces
and non-standard APIs that it violates.

I still don't understand what we're doing about copyright notices.

Change-Id: Ic99d8c42037c9fe4af68e2dfeee6067e8aaac829

commit_message:
Base class for storage servers

DRY out storage server code a bit.  We opt *not* to have all the HTTP
methods in common use defined as "not implemented" since one does not
have to implement them.  We also ensure 100% coverage of the
common/test_server.py module using just common/test_server.py.

Change-Id: Idabe8e4c99415f0bedba93890300d5416626af3f

Tiny little last-minute changes

operations/backup -- made this a top-level head and fixed the
bullet lists

terminology:
amqp -- fixed bad reference list formatting

commit_message:
Return an error exit code if config is missing on start

Previously, we fixed a silent error in case pipeline was invalid in
the config. This is plugged elsewhere and is different: the Manager
class does not even attempt to load anything.

Note that this may be visible as a nonzero exit code from
"swift-init start all" and the like, if any server in the group
is missing. The command starts servers just like before, but
reports a status if anything was missing. This may trip shell
scripts that do set -e.

Change-Id: I55419d910bfa7cd13f537d1c10e3e32db77bda1f

commit_message:
Allow get_account and get_container to return an iterator

The full_listing option of get_account and get_container
builds and returns a list of accounts or containers that may
be really large.

To reduce memory consumption this patch adds the
full_listing_iter parameter that returns
an iterator instead of the a list of the full listing.
The caller will be able to consume it safely regarding
the memory usage.

This patch updates the full listing option of get_account
and get_container to use the iterators but keep the
compatibility by returning a list. This avoid
code duplication.

Change-Id: Ie4e394df2b323d8aa2665a9b13c49d4db9d1e0a9

commit_message:
Bypass committing pending records from .pending file

In swift-{account, container}-info, get_info method call
commits all pending records found in .pending db file.
So this change will alllow user to bypass it with
new command line option.

Change-Id: Icfb412023ef2f3e58380146ad8a68f04457ebe0f

commit_message:
Zabbix documentation

planning/4450-monitoring -- main section for the monitoring tools.
Will eventurally introduce Ceilometer/MongoDB and Zabbix then source in
the individual files with details.

planning/monitoring/zabbix.rst -- information about planning for zabbix

Deleted operations/8550-zabbix -- how to use the dashboard and set templates

ref-arch/8100-zabbix.rst -- internals of Zabbix implementation

user-guide/config-environment/8000-zabbix-access.rst presents the
Settings page used to reset the Zabbix password.

terminology/z/zabbix -- terminology article

Note:  The screen where one assigns Zabbix to a role is in a different
commit so does not show in this commit at this time.

Change-Id: I6bac22838ccee596327508cb69df59b0aa49e7ee

Changing 'httpd' to 'web server' to be less specific

to 'web server'.

commit_message:
Add support for OSprofiler

To be able to create profiling traces for Heat, the client should be
able to send special HTTP header that contains trace info.

Change-Id: I2ff833fac2dfe3bb0fcbd6a31c210db2935b72f1
Closes-bug: #1363782

commit_message:
glusterfs: edit config option specifying volume

glusterfs driver has an option to specify the GlusterFS volume to be
mounted on the Manila host. The GlusterFS volume to be mounted is
presently specified in a file, whose path is the config option
glusterfs_volumes_config. Instead have a string valued config option
in manila.conf that directly takes the same input.

Change-Id: I3f8734174db71ef232620c55d4ecdd2b5d0192ad
Closes-Bug: #1365941

commit_message:
Fix error adding security groups to instances with nexus

Adding security group for running instance should not
invoke the nexus plugin. Current implementation does not
validate for the 'new_host_id' as assumes it as host migration
and fails.
Closes-Bug: #1365226

Change-Id: I9ab6b8438e6ee0698a8e2ae7ff7736f7c71b2370

[{'created': '2014-09-18 00:26:08.000000000', 'message': "Verify requested size in volume.api create

Currently we're not checking that the input value requested
for size on volume create is valid, but taskflow portion of
the code expects it and as a result when it receives invalid
input we litter the logs with Trace messages.

This patch adds a check of the size requeste on create in the
volume.api code so we can return a proper exception to the caller
and minimizing how far down the path we need to go in order to fail.

Valid size argument requires input is an int and greater than zero.

Closes-Bug: 1370773

Change-Id: I41a7fce9a5be6e11140977853b14b68ea5c110d3
"}]
commit_message:
Verify requested size in volume.api create

Currently we're not checking that the input value requested
for size on volume create is valid, but taskflow portion of
the code expects it and as a result when it receives invalid
input we litter the logs with Trace messages.

This patch adds a check of the size requeste on create in the
volume.api code so we can return a proper exception to the caller
and minimizing how far down the path we need to go in order to fail.

Valid size argument requires input is an int and greater than zero.

Closes-Bug: 1370773

Change-Id: I41a7fce9a5be6e11140977853b14b68ea5c110d3

[{'created': '2014-09-13 07:42:18.000000000', 'message': "Stop using intersphinx

Remove intersphinx from the docs build as it triggers network calls that
occasionally fail, and we don't really use intersphinx (links other
sphinx documents out on the internet)

This also removes the requirement for internet access during docs build.

This can cause docs jobs to fail if the project errors out on
warnings.

Change-Id: I71e941e2a639641a662a163c682eb86d51de42fb
Related-Bug: #1368910
"}]
commit_message:
Stop using intersphinx

Remove intersphinx from the docs build as it triggers network calls that
occasionally fail, and we don't really use intersphinx (links other
sphinx documents out on the internet)

This also removes the requirement for internet access during docs build.

This can cause docs jobs to fail if the project errors out on
warnings.

Change-Id: I71e941e2a639641a662a163c682eb86d51de42fb
Related-Bug: #1368910

commit_message:
Add stack-update argument for reset parameters

A new argument named clear-parameter for stack-update
will be supported by the heat engine to reset the value of the
parameter back to the default value. This argument can be
specified multiple times.

Partially-implements: blueprint troubleshooting-low-level-control
Partial-Bug: 1224828
Change-Id: Ib04dbc13978fdefd1bf3485f2654e139a3f1df8d

commit_message:
Add stack-update argument for patching parameters

A new argument named existing for stack-update will be
supported by the heat engine to use the parameters stored
in the Db.

Partially-implements: blueprint troubleshooting-low-level-control
Partial-Bug: 1224828
Change-Id: I30a2b223d7dd19a717ed989b419b1e6cb2ac143b

commit_message:
Handle federated tokens

Federated tokens don't include domains in the user object.
Keystoneclient should be able to estimate whether the token is a
federated one and, if so, don't expect user domain information.
In case of the federated token keystoneclient returns None in response
to user_domain_name and user_domain_id calls.

Co-Authored-By: Steve Martinelli <stevemar@ca.ibm.com>

Closes-Bug: #1346820
Change-Id: I3453275fa1b0a41b1c015b0c3a92895a77d69a41

commit_message:
Add a memory based shared cache

Simple dictionary based shared cache to speed up not just
a single set of nested wsdl/xsd(s) but also to share the
same cache, so when the same initial wsdl is loaded again
we still use the cached data from the previous wsdl load.
We essentially take the hit on the first wsdl load and
subsequent loads will be much faster. The cached items
expire in an hour to both clean up memory as well as
switch to newer wsdl/xsd(s) when the vCenter is upgraded
without needed a forced restart of nova compute process.

Change-Id: Ia2265f1f8ed5fe8b05770a5572f1516893b532a0

1. The way I envisioned atomic status updates is as part of tasks.  For example, in create_volume, I would have transitions like this: (1) create new volume entry, (2) atomically reserve quota and change to creating_quota_reserved status, (3) call driver and change to creating_driver_called, and then (4) update quota, model_update, status, and anything else atomically.  This code will not work for things like step 2 and 4 (which I believe are the common case, or will be once we have recovery/state machine).

2. Why won't this work with galera deployments?  I think that a lot of "real" deployments use it - bad enough we don't test it, but we shouldn't put it code that we know breaks it.

Thanks for this first step though!'}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2014-09-18 01:32:14.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

commit_message:
Add in atomic volume status updating

In order to be able to use the newly created state transitions
and validation functions, we need to create a backend db api
that allows us to *atomically* read, validate, then update the
status to the transitions desired end status.

This does use the with_lockmode() to do this, which it seems
like cinder is already using to do this in an atomic manner.

This will likely *not* work with current galera deployments.

Part of blueprint cinder-state-enforcer

Change-Id: I72b77461c27ac6c1d331563b74e23aa3e5054c2a

commit_message:
Add a throttled scenario runner

Add a runner which can execute at a given rate for a given
number of scenario calls using a thread backed pool. This
allows for precise control over the rate at which scenarios
are ran.

Change-Id: I43bb60646df01713618dbf44915cbe550ed3d85a

I think Kevin meant to drop a -1 on this, so I'll do it so that it doesn't look unreviewed to people (like myself) walking through the queue.

I agree with Kevin's about the mocking, by the way. Many issues can arise from forcibly replacing bits of an implementation in a test like that. If anything ever becomes a singleton or global, then we've got interaction problems between the tests. It's not the way to use mock.

It looks like many of the other tests do the same thing. When you resubmit, could you split these up into separate (dependent) patches? I think if you put the small ones at the front we could get those merged much quicker as we look at the larger ones in more detail."}, {'account_id': 3185, 'date': '2013-10-16 14:49:11.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

[{'created': '2013-09-30 13:46:20.000000000', 'message': 'Adds additional Hyper-V driver unit tests

This patch adds a consistent amount of unit tests for the *utils classes

Removes unnecessary instructions in test_hypervapi

Lines have no actual effect on the tests. Removing them
will facilitate further unit tests.

Partial-Bug: #1220256

commit_message:
libvirt: Don't cache base image while migration

We should cache base image only if the disk file of instance is
not exists. while migration the disk is an whole one without
backing file even if it is qcow2 format, so nova needn't to
cache base image for instance, otherwise if the Glance image
is deleted, an ImageNotFound exception will be raised.
Here we also add target image exists checking after getting the
lock, otherwise we may get a broken image.

Closes-bug: #1298216
Closes-bug: #1298420
Change-Id: Ic10eb5f0027ff0647928dc04afaeb70c6593544b

commit_message:
Network: enable instance deletion when dhcp release fails

In the event that the 'dhcp_release' fails we should continue
with the deletion of the instance.

This will no longer the leave the instance in ERROR state.

Change-Id: Ie8259180a9df12865940907c728a8d9da3c9fda0
Closes-bug: #1289397

commit_message:
Support a common cache for metadata

Currently, the Nova metadata API stores its cache in memory, which
prevents it from being shared amongst multiple hypervisors and thus
reduces the hit rate. This blueprint proposes to optionally replace
the in-memory cache with dogpile.cache, allowing cache sharing between
hypervisors.

Change-Id: I7b2f6d3fd6408d0220439d8c74f5e1af22bb0583

commit_message:
Fix concurrency issue with HeatStack.push

All changes to template made with call HeatStack.updateTemplate
while HeatStack.push is in progress will be lost after HeatStack.push
will be finished.

Co-Authored-By: Stan Lagun <slagun@mirantis.com>
Closes-bug: #1370503
Change-Id: Ia5c0457a2841bbcb30bc60f5ab99f7872a77b51e

commit_message:
javelin-resources: attach a volume to a server

In tempest/javelin2, we want to attach a volume to a server. For that we
need to bind the attachment in the resources.yaml.
Also, adding another volume to be sure we can create 2 volumes and
attach them to 2 differents instances.

Prereq for blueprint:javelin2
Change-Id: I71be5c0a2af69706f38f9f3a049d5591d838d8c0
Signed-off-by: Emilien Macchi <emilien.macchi@enovance.com>

commit_message:
Allow users to clean up role assignments

This change allows users the ability to remove role assignments in the
event the user has been removed from the backend.

Closes-Bug: #1321378
Change-Id: I895e6e9718bc48344a53f192d5d56e6990da888e

commit_message:
Sync latest process and str utils from oslo

This backport the necessary changes to fix both issues:
* Make execute method clean password in exception
* Make sure mask_password works properly

Backport in oslo-incubator: 4cf1a2a158f7c3c21799bf2e6ba0e7b5fbc25d62

Closes-Bug: 1343604
Closes-Bug: 1345233
SecurityImpact

Change-Id: I3b49b1d667f6ade9ae3f6765d735440a3e838917

commit_message:
secgroup-create description is not optional

The description field to the Nova API for secgroup
create is not optional. This enforces the supplying
of the description field in novaclient as the Nova
call will fail if it is not supplied.

v3 version does not need to be updated as it was never
changed.

Change-Id: I6fc823990190b935a8e1214efc8c3ac3a0941abf
Closes-Bug: 1367121

commit_message:
Use VMware xsd and wsdl from oslo.vmware 0.5.0

The SPBM XSD and WSDL files are currently in the driver folder in
Cinder. The 0.5.0 release of oslo.vmware contains these files, so
Cinder can use them.

This patch is removing these files from Cinder and adds the
dependency to oslo.vmware.

Change-Id: I8250dd0adc28cc3859221be5d52bd46f2a88a677

commit_message:
Update nova content for Juno

I updated nova content in the installation guide for Juno
as follows:

1) Removed prompts specific to MySQL because most distributions
   will use MariaDB.
2) Explicitly created endpoint with 'regionOne' region to avoid
   inconsistent defaults.
3) Replaced 'auth_*' keys with 'identity_uri' key.
4) Moved glance configuration to [glance] section.
5) Recommended enabling verbose logging.
6) Added example command output and updated existing command
   output.

Change-Id: Iad5c20e6562bcab83c6f0d5efccab566b3c18eae

commit_message:
Fix safe_encode func in strutils

Function 'safe_encode ' in 'strutils' module treats
'UTF-8' and 'utf-8' encodings as different.
But it should understand different aliases,
that have different text cases.

Change-Id: Ia080328a863318c852665f32d5fa1e5824f86d5d
Closes-Bug: #1342050

commit_message:
Add cpu_time in notification

This change adds a new polling task to retrieve the cpu_time of each
instances and stores thel in database.

And it will add this new information to the notification.

Partial implements usage-data-in-notification

Change-Id: I8e515c27e034156d9f263ef6660bd3047b0d5fe1

commit_message:
Fix autogenerate-config-docs link

Clicking the link to autogenerate-config-docs opens a blank page.
This patch fixes the link.

Change-Id: I60ca664de3f630058b8ce8e5a32340faf213d54b
